# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rocket
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard's work as both theorist and engineer anticipated many of the developments that would make spaceflight possible.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He has been called the man who ushered in the Space Age.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Two of Goddard's 214 patented inventions, a multi-stage rocket (1914), and a liquid-fuel rocket (1914), were important milestones toward spaceflight.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] His 1919 monograph *A Method of Reaching Extreme Altitudes* is considered one of the classic texts of 20th-century rocket science.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard successfully pioneered modern methods such as two-axis control (gyroscopes and steerable thrust) to allow rockets to control their flight effectively.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Although his work in the field was revolutionary, Goddard received little public or financial support for his research and development work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He was a shy person, and rocket research was not considered a suitable pursuit for a physics professor.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The press and other scientists ridiculed his theories of spaceflight.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] As a result, he became protective of his privacy and his work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Years after his death, at the dawn of the Space Age, Goddard came to be recognized as one of the founding fathers of modern rocketry, along with Robert Esnault-Pelterie, Konstantin Tsiolkovsky and Hermann Oberth.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He not only recognized early on the potential of rockets for atmospheric research, ballistic missiles and space travel, but also was the first to scientifically study, design, construct and fly the precursory rockets needed to eventually implement those ideas.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center was named in Goddard's honor in 1959.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He was also inducted into the International Aerospace Hall of Fame and National Aviation Hall of Fame in 1966, and the International Space Hall of Fame in 1976.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard was born in Worcester, Massachusetts, to Nahum Danford Goddard (1859–1928) and Fannie Louise Hoyt (1864–1920).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Robert was their only child to survive; a younger son, Richard Henry, was born with a spinal deformity and died before his first birthday.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] His father Nahum was employed by manufacturers and invented several useful tools.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard had English paternal family roots in New England with William Goddard (1628–91) a London grocer who settled in Watertown, Massachusetts, in 1666.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] On his maternal side he was descended from John Hoyt and other settlers of Massachusetts in the late 1600s.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Shortly after his birth, the family moved to Boston.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] With a curiosity about nature, he studied the heavens using a telescope from his father and observed the birds flying.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Essentially a country boy, he loved the outdoors and hiking with his father on trips to Worcester and became an excellent marksman with a rifle.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In 1898, his mother contracted tuberculosis and they moved back to Worcester for the clear air.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] On Sundays, the family attended the Episcopal church, and Robert sang in the choir.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] With the electrification of American cities in the 1880s, the young Goddard became interested in science—specifically, engineering and technology.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] When his father showed him how to generate static electricity on the family's carpet, the five-year-old's imagination was sparked.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Robert experimented, believing he could jump higher if the zinc from a battery could be charged by scuffing his feet on the gravel walk.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] But, holding the zinc, he could jump no higher than usual.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard halted the experiments after a warning from his mother that if he succeeded, he could "go sailing away and might not be able to come back." He experimented with chemicals and created a cloud of smoke and an explosion in the house.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard's father encouraged Robert's scientific interest further by providing him with a telescope, a microscope, and a subscription to *Scientific American*.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Robert developed a fascination with flight, first with kites and then with balloons.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He became a thorough diarist and documenter of his work—a skill that would greatly benefit his later career.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] These interests merged at age 16, when Goddard attempted to construct a balloon out of aluminum, shaping the raw metal in his home workshop, and filling it with hydrogen.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] After nearly five weeks of methodical, documented efforts, he finally abandoned the project, remarking, "... balloon will not go up. ...
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Failior [*sic*] crowns enterprise." However, the lesson of this failure did not restrain Goddard's growing determination and confidence in his work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He became interested in space at the age of 16 when he read H.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Wells' newly published novel *The War of the Worlds,* in which England is invaded by an alien species from Mars.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] His dedication to pursuing space flight became fixed on October 19, 1899.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The 17-year-old Goddard climbed a cherry tree to cut off dead limbs.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He was transfixed by the sky, and his imagination grew.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] For the rest of his life, he observed October 19 as "Anniversary Day", a private commemoration of the day of his greatest inspiration.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The young Goddard was a thin and frail boy, almost always in fragile health.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He suffered from stomach problems, pleurisy, colds, and bronchitis, and he fell two years behind his classmates.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He became a voracious reader, regularly visiting the local public library to borrow books on the physical sciences.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard's interest in aerodynamics led him to study some of Samuel Langley's scientific papers in the periodical *Smithsonian*.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In these papers, Langley wrote that birds flap their wings with different force on each side to turn in the air.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Inspired by these articles, the teenage Goddard watched swallows and chimney swifts from the porch of his home, noting how subtly the birds moved their wings to control their flight.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He noted how remarkably the birds controlled their flight with their tail feathers, which he called the birds' equivalent of ailerons.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He took exception to some of Langley's conclusions and in 1901 wrote a letter to *St.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Nicholas* declined to publish Goddard's letter, remarking that birds fly with a certain amount of intelligence and that "machines will not act with such intelligence." Goddard disagreed, believing that a man could control a flying machine with his own intelligence.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Around this time, Goddard read Newton's *Principia Mathematica*, and found that Newton's third law of motion applied to motion in space.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] As his health improved, Goddard continued his formal schooling as a 19-year-old sophomore at South High in Worcester in 1901.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He excelled in his coursework, and his peers twice elected him class president.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Making up for lost time, he studied books on mathematics, astronomy, mechanics and composition from the school library.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] At his graduation ceremony in 1904, he gave his class oration as valedictorian.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard enrolled at Worcester Polytechnic Institute in 1904.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He quickly impressed the head of the physics department, A.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Wilmer Duff, with his thirst for knowledge, and Duff took him on as a laboratory assistant and tutor.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] At WPI, Goddard joined the Sigma Alpha Epsilon fraternity and began a long courtship with high school classmate Miriam Olmstead, an honor student who had graduated with him as salutatorian.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Eventually, she and Goddard were engaged, but they drifted apart and ended the engagement around 1909.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard received his B.S. degree in physics from Worcester Polytechnic in 1908, and after serving there for a year as an instructor in physics, he began his graduate studies at Clark University in Worcester in the fall of 1909.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] While studying at Clark, Goddard continued working in Salisbury Labs at WPI and anecdotally caused a damaging explosion, whereupon his work was moved to the Magnetic Lab (today called Skull Tomb).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard received his M.A. degree in physics from Clark University in 1910, and then stayed at Clark to complete his Ph.D. in physics in 1911.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He spent another year at Clark as an honorary fellow in physics, and in 1912 he accepted a research fellowship at Princeton University's Palmer Physical Laboratory.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The high-school student summed up his ideas on space travel in a proposed article, "The Navigation of Space," which he submitted to the *Popular Science News*.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] While still an undergraduate, Goddard wrote a paper proposing a method for balancing airplanes using gyro-stabilization.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He submitted the idea to *Scientific American*, which published the paper in 1907.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard later wrote in his diaries that he believed his paper was the first proposal of a way to automatically stabilize aircraft in flight.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] His proposal came around the same time as other scientists were making breakthroughs in developing functional gyroscopes.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] While studying physics at WPI, ideas came to Goddard's mind that sometimes seemed impossible, but he was compelled to record them for future investigation.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He wrote that "there was something inside which simply would not stop working." He purchased some cloth-covered notebooks and began filling them with a variety of thoughts, mostly concerning his dream of space travel.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He considered centrifugal force, radio waves, magnetic reaction, solar energy, atomic energy, ion or electrostatic propulsion and other methods to reach space.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] After experimenting with solid-fuel rockets he was convinced by 1909 that chemical-propellant engines were the answer.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] A particularly complex concept was set down in June 1908: Sending a camera around distant planets, guided by measurements of gravity along the trajectory, and returning to earth.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] His first writing on the possibility of a liquid-fueled rocket came on February 2, 1909.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard had begun to study ways of increasing a rocket's efficiency using methods differing from conventional solid-fuel rockets.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He wrote in his notebook about using liquid hydrogen as a fuel with liquid oxygen as the oxidizer.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He believed that 50-percent efficiency could be achieved with these liquid propellants (i.e., half of the heat energy of combustion converted to the kinetic energy of the exhaust gases).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In the decades around 1910, radio was a new technology, fertile for innovation.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In 1912, while working at Princeton University, Goddard investigated the effects of radio waves on insulators.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In order to generate radio-frequency power, he invented a vacuum tube with a beam deflection that operated like a cathode-ray oscillator tube.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] His patent on this tube, which predated that of Lee De Forest, became central in the suit between Arthur A.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Collins, whose small company made radio transmitter tubes, and AT&T and RCA over his use of vacuum tube technology.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard accepted only a consultant's fee from Collins when the suit was dropped.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Eventually, the two big companies allowed the country's growing electronics industry to use the De Forest patents freely.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] By 1912 he had in his spare time, using calculus, developed the mathematics which allowed him to calculate the position and velocity of a rocket in vertical flight, given the weight of the rocket and weight of the propellant and the velocity (with respect to the rocket frame) of the exhaust gases.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In effect he had independently developed the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation published a decade earlier in Russia.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Tsiolkovsky, however, did not account for gravity nor drag.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] For vertical flight from the surface of Earth Goddard included in his differential equation the effects of gravity and aerodynamic drag.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He wrote: "An approximate method was found necessary ... in order to avoid an unsolved problem in the calculus of variations.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The solution that was obtained revealed the fact that surprisingly small initial masses would be necessary ...
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] His first goal was to build a sounding rocket with which to study the atmosphere.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Not only would such investigation aid meteorology, but it was necessary to determine temperature, density and wind speed as functions of altitude in order to design efficient space launch vehicles.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In early 1913, Goddard became seriously ill with tuberculosis and had to leave his position at Princeton.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He then returned to Worcester, where he began a prolonged process of recovery at home.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He decided he should spend time outside in the fresh air and walk for exercise, and he gradually improved.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] It was during this period of recuperation, however, that Goddard began to produce some of his most important work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] As his symptoms subsided, he allowed himself to work an hour per day with his notes made at Princeton.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He was afraid that nobody would be able to read his scribbling should he succumb.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In the technological and manufacturing atmosphere of Worcester, patents were considered essential, not only to protect original work but as documentation of first discovery.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He began to see the importance of his ideas as intellectual property, and thus began to secure those ideas before someone else did—and he would have to pay to use them.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In May 1913, he wrote descriptions concerning his first rocket patent applications.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] His father brought them to a patent lawyer in Worcester who helped him to refine his ideas for consideration.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard's first patent application was submitted in October 1913.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In 1914, his first two landmark patents were accepted and registered.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The first, U.S. patent 1,102,653, described a multi-stage rocket fueled with a solid "explosive material." The second, U.S. patent 1,103,503, described a rocket fueled with a solid fuel (explosive material) or with liquid propellants (gasoline and liquid nitrous oxide).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The two patents would eventually become important milestones in the history of rocketry.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Overall, 214 patents were published, some posthumously by his wife.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In the fall of 1914 Goddard's health had improved, and he accepted a part-time position as an instructor and research fellow at Clark University.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] His position at Clark allowed him to further his rocketry research.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He ordered numerous supplies that could be used to build rocket prototypes for launch and spent much of 1915 in preparation for his first tests.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard's first test launch of a powder rocket came on an early evening in 1915 following his daytime classes at Clark.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The launch was loud and bright enough to arouse the alarm of the campus janitor, and Goddard had to reassure him that his experiments, while being serious study, were also quite harmless.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] After this incident Goddard took his experiments inside the physics lab in order to limit any disturbance.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] At the Clark physics lab, Goddard conducted static tests of powder rockets to measure their thrust and efficiency.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He found his earlier estimates to be verified; powder rockets were converting only about two percent of the thermal energy in their fuel into thrust and kinetic energy.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] At this point he applied de Laval nozzles, which were generally used with steam turbine engines, and these greatly improved efficiency.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Connecting a combustion chamber full of gunpowder to various converging-diverging expansion (de Laval) nozzles, Goddard was able in static tests to achieve engine efficiencies of more than 63% and exhaust velocities of over 7,000 feet (2,134 meters) per second.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Few would recognize it at the time, but this little engine was a major breakthrough.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] These experiments suggested that rockets could be made powerful enough to escape Earth and travel into space.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] This engine and subsequent experiments sponsored by the Smithsonian Institution were the beginning of modern rocketry and, ultimately, space exploration.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard realized, however, that it would take the more efficient liquid propellants to reach space.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Later that year, Goddard designed an elaborate experiment at the Clark physics lab and proved that a rocket would perform in a vacuum such as that in space.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He believed it would, but many other scientists were not yet convinced.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] His experiment demonstrated that a rocket's performance actually decreases under atmospheric pressure.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In September 1906 he wrote in his notebook about using the repulsion of electrically charged particles (ions) to produce thrust.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] From 1916 to 1917, Goddard built and tested the first known experimental ion thrusters, which he thought might be used for propulsion in the near-vacuum conditions of outer space.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The small glass engines he built were tested at atmospheric pressure, where they generated a stream of ionized air.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] By 1916, the cost of Goddard's rocket research had become too great for his modest teaching salary to bear.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He began to solicit potential sponsors for financial assistance, beginning with the Smithsonian Institution, the National Geographic Society, and the Aero Club of America.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In his letter to the Smithsonian in September 1916, Goddard claimed he had achieved a 63% efficiency and a nozzle velocity of almost 2438 meters per second.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] With these performance levels, he believed a rocket could vertically lift a weight of 1 lb (0.45 kg) to a height of 232 miles (373 km) with an initial launch weight of only 89.6 lbs (40.64 kg).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The Smithsonian was interested and asked Goddard to elaborate upon his initial inquiry.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard responded with a detailed manuscript he had already prepared, entitled *A Method of Reaching Extreme Altitudes*.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In January 1917, the Smithsonian agreed to provide Goddard with a five-year grant totaling US$5000.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Afterward, Clark was able to contribute US$3500 and the use of their physics lab to the project.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Worcester Polytechnic Institute also allowed him to use its abandoned Magnetics Laboratory on the edge of campus during this time, as a safe place for testing.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] WPI also made some parts in their machine shop.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard's fellow Clark scientists were astonished at the unusually large Smithsonian grant for rocket research, which they thought was not real science.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Decades later, rocket scientists who knew how much it cost to research and develop rockets said that he had received little financial support.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Two years later, at the insistence of Arthur G.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Webster, the world-renowned head of Clark's physics department, Goddard arranged for the Smithsonian to publish the paper, *A Method...,* which documented his work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] While at Clark University, Goddard did research into solar power using a parabolic dish to concentrate the Sun's rays on a machined piece of quartz, that was sprayed with mercury, which then heated water and drove an electric generator.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard believed his invention had overcome all the obstacles that had previously defeated other scientists and inventors, and he had his findings published in the November 1929 issue of *Popular Science*.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Not all of Goddard's early work was geared toward space travel.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] As the United States entered World War I in 1917, the country's universities began to lend their services to the war effort.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard believed his rocket research could be applied to many different military applications, including mobile artillery, field weapons and naval torpedoes.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] No record exists in his papers of any interest by the Navy to Goddard's inquiry.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] However, Army Ordnance was quite interested, and Goddard met several times with Army personnel.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] During this time, Goddard was also contacted, in early 1918, by a civilian industrialist in Worcester about the possibility of manufacturing rockets for the military.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] However, as the businessman's enthusiasm grew, so did Goddard's suspicion.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Talks eventually broke down as Goddard began to fear his work might be appropriated by the business.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] However, an Army Signal Corps officer tried to make Goddard cooperate, but he was called off by General George Squier of the Signal Corps who had been contacted by Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution, Charles Walcott.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard became leery of working with corporations and was careful to secure patents to "protect his ideas." These events led to the Signal Corps sponsorship of Goddard's work during World War I.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard proposed to the Army an idea for a tube-based rocket launcher as a light infantry weapon.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The launcher concept became the precursor to the bazooka.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The rocket-powered, recoil-free weapon was the brainchild of Goddard as a side project (under Army contract) of his work on rocket propulsion.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard, during his tenure at Clark University, and working at Mount Wilson Observatory for security reasons, designed the tube-fired rocket for military use during World War I.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Hickman successfully demonstrated his rocket to the U.S.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Army Signal Corps at Aberdeen Proving Ground, Maryland, on November 6, 1918, using two music stands for a launch platform.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The Army was impressed, but the Compiègne Armistice was signed only five days later, and further development was discontinued as World War I ended.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The delay in the development of the bazooka and other weapons was a result of the long recovery period required from Goddard's serious bout with tuberculosis.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard continued to be a part-time consultant to the U.S.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Government at Indian Head, Maryland, until 1923, but his focus had turned to other research involving rocket propulsion, including work with liquid fuels and liquid oxygen.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Later, the former Clark University researcher Clarence N.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Edward Uhl continued Goddard's work on the bazooka.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] A shaped-charge warhead was attached to the rocket, leading to the tank-killing weapon used in World War II and to many other powerful rocket weapons.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In 1919 Goddard thought that it would be premature to disclose the results of his experiments because his engine was not sufficiently developed.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Webster realized that Goddard had accomplished a good deal of fine work and insisted that Goddard publish his progress so far or he would take care of it himself, so Goddard asked the Smithsonian Institution if it would publish the report, updated with notes, that he had submitted in late 1916.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In late 1919, the Smithsonian published Goddard's groundbreaking work, *A Method of Reaching Extreme Altitudes*.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The report describes Goddard's mathematical theories of rocket flight, his experiments with solid-fuel rockets, and the possibilities he saw of exploring Earth's atmosphere and beyond.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Along with Konstantin Tsiolkovsky's earlier work, *The Exploration of Cosmic Space by Means of Reaction Devices*, Goddard's report is regarded as one of the pioneering works of the science of rocketry, and 1750 copies were distributed worldwide.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard also sent a copy to individuals who requested one, until his personal supply was exhausted.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard described extensive experiments with solid-fuel rocket engines burning high-grade nitrocellulose smokeless powder.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] A critical breakthrough was the use of the steam turbine nozzle invented by the Swedish inventor Gustaf de Laval.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The de Laval nozzle allows the most efficient (isentropic) conversion of the energy of hot gases into forward motion.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] By means of this nozzle, Goddard increased the efficiency of his rocket engines from two percent to 64 percent and obtained supersonic exhaust velocities of over Mach 7.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Included as a thought experiment was the idea of launching a rocket to the Moon and igniting a mass of flash powder on its surface, so as to be visible through a telescope.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He discussed the matter seriously, down to an estimate of the amount of powder required.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard's conclusion was that a rocket with starting mass of 3.21 tons could produce a flash "just visible" from Earth, assuming a final payload weight of 10.7 pounds.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard eschewed publicity, because he did not have time to reply to criticism of his work, and his imaginative ideas about space travel were shared only with private groups he trusted.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In that same letter, Goddard clearly describes the concept of the ablative heat shield, suggesting the landing apparatus be covered with "layers of a very infusible hard substance with layers of a poor heat conductor between" designed to erode in the same way as the surface of a meteor.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The publication of Goddard's document gained him national attention from U.S. newspapers, most of it negative.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Even the Smithsonian had to abstain from publicity because of the amount of ridiculous correspondence received from the general public.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] On January 13, 1920, the day after its front-page story about Goddard's rocket, an unsigned *New York Times* editorial, in a section entitled "Topics of the Times", scoffed at the proposal.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In 1924, Goddard published an article, "How my speed rocket can propel itself in vacuum", in *Popular Science*, in which he explained the physics and gave details of the vacuum experiments he had performed to prove the theory.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] But, no matter how he tried to explain his results, he was not understood by the majority.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Though the public laughed at the "moon man," his paper was read seriously by many rocketeers in America, Europe, and Russia who were stirred to build their own rockets.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard worked alone with just his team of mechanics and machinists for many years.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] This was a result of the harsh criticism from the media and other scientists, and his understanding of the military applications which foreign powers might use.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard became increasingly suspicious of others and often worked alone, except during the two World Wars, which limited the impact of much of his work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Another limiting factor was the lack of support from the American government, military and academia, all failing to understand the value of the rocket to study the atmosphere and near space, and for military applications.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In Europe the rocketeers were mainly theorists and visionaries.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard was the foremost experimenter, and his report was responsible for encouraging many to build their own rockets.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] As Germany became ever more war-like, Goddard refused to communicate with German rocket experimenters, though he received more and more of their correspondence.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Oberth had Goddard's 1919 paper translated and Wernher von Braun read it.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] They therefore knew that efficiencies at least thirty times greater than conventional rockets were achievable with Goddard's engine design.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Via von Braun and his team joining the US post-war programs there is thus an indirect line of scientific and technology tradition from NASA back to Goddard.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Forty-nine years after its editorial mocking Goddard, on July 17, 1969—the day after the launch of Apollo 11—*The New York Times* published a short item under the headline "A Correction".
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The rocket equation indicates that the lighter a rocket's structure is, the greater its final velocity will be, as more of its mass can consist of the propellants.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard strove to reduce the mass of his rockets (total mass minus propellant mass).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Liquid propellants would enable the combustion chambers to be smaller and lighter.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He began considering liquid propellants, including hydrogen and oxygen, as early as 1909.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He knew that hydrogen and oxygen was the most efficient fuel/oxidizer combination.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] However, liquid hydrogen was not readily available in 1921, when he abandoned solid fuel, and he selected gasoline as the safest, cheapest fuel to handle.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard began experimenting with liquid oxidizer, liquid fuel rockets in September 1921, and successfully tested the first liquid propellant engine in November 1923.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] It had a cylindrical combustion chamber, using impinging jets to mix and atomize liquid oxygen and gasoline.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In 1924–25, Goddard had problems developing a high-pressure piston pump to send fuel to the combustion chamber.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He wanted to scale up the experiments, but his funding would not allow such growth.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He decided to forgo the pumps and use a pressurized fuel feed system applying pressure to the fuel tank from a tank of inert gas, a technique that is still used today.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The liquid oxygen, some of which evaporated, provided its own pressure.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] On December 6, 1925, he tested the simpler pressure feed system.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He conducted a static test on the firing stand at the Clark University physics laboratory.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The engine successfully lifted its own weight in a 27-second test in the static rack.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] It was a major success for Goddard, proving that a liquid fuel rocket was possible.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The test moved Goddard an important step closer to launching a rocket with liquid fuel.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard conducted an additional test in December, and two more in January 1926.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] After that, he began preparing for a possible launch of the rocket system.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard launched the world's first liquid-fueled (gasoline and liquid oxygen) rocket on March 16, 1926, in Auburn, Massachusetts.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Present at the launch were his crew chief Henry Sachs, Esther Goddard, and Percy Roope, who was Clark's assistant professor in the physics department.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The rocket, which was later dubbed "Nell", rose just 41 feet (12.5 meters) during a 2.5-second flight that ended 184 feet (56 meters) away in a cabbage field, but it was an important demonstration that liquid fuels and oxidizers were possible propellants for larger rockets.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The launch site is now a National Historic Landmark, the Goddard Rocket Launching Site.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Viewers familiar with more modern rocket designs may find it difficult to distinguish the rocket from its launching apparatus in the well-known picture of "Nell".
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The complete rocket is significantly taller than Goddard but does not include the pyramidal support structure which he is grasping.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The rocket's combustion chamber is the small cylinder at the top; the nozzle is visible beneath it.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The fuel tank, which is also part of the rocket, is the larger cylinder opposite Goddard's torso.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The fuel tank is directly beneath the nozzle and is protected from the motor's exhaust by an asbestos cone.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Asbestos-wrapped aluminum tubes connect the motor to the tanks, providing both support and fuel transport.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] This layout is no longer used, since the experiment showed that this was no more stable than placing the combustion chamber and nozzle at the base.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] By May, after a series of modifications to simplify the plumbing, the combustion chamber and nozzle were placed in the now classic position, at the lower end of the rocket.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard determined early that fins alone were not sufficient to stabilize the rocket in flight and keep it on the desired trajectory in the face of winds aloft and other disturbing forces.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He added movable vanes in the exhaust, controlled by a gyroscope, to control and steer his rocket.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] (The Germans used this technique in their V-2.) He also introduced the more efficient swiveling engine in several rockets, basically the method used to steer large liquid-propellant missiles and launchers today.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] After launch of one of Goddard's rockets in July 1929 again gained the attention of the newspapers, Charles Lindbergh learned of his work in a *New York Times* article.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] At the time, Lindbergh had begun to wonder what would become of aviation (even space flight) in the distant future and had settled on jet propulsion and rocket flight as a probable next step.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] After checking with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) and being assured that Goddard was a bona fide physicist and not a crackpot, he phoned Goddard in November 1929.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard met the aviator soon after in his office at Clark University.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Upon meeting Goddard, Lindbergh was immediately impressed by his research, and Goddard was similarly impressed by the flier's interest.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He discussed his work openly with Lindbergh, forming an alliance that would last for the rest of his life.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] While having long since become reluctant to share his ideas, Goddard showed complete openness with those few who shared his dream, and whom he felt he could trust.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] By late 1929, Goddard had been attracting additional notoriety with each rocket launch.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He was finding it increasingly difficult to conduct his research without unwanted distractions.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Lindbergh discussed finding additional financing for Goddard's work and lent his famous name to Goddard's work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In 1930 Lindbergh made several proposals to industry and private investors for funding, which proved all but impossible to find following the recent U.S. stock market crash in October 1929.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In the spring of 1930, Lindbergh finally found an ally in the Guggenheim family.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Financier Daniel Guggenheim agreed to fund Goddard's research over the next four years for a total of $100,000 (~$2.4 million today).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The Guggenheim family, especially Harry Guggenheim, would continue to support Goddard's work in the years to come.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Because of the military potential of the rocket, Goddard, Lindbergh, Harry Guggenheim, the Smithsonian Institution and others tried in 1940, before the U.S. entered World War II, to convince the Army and Navy of its value.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard's services were offered, but there was no interest, initially.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Two young, imaginative military officers eventually got the services to attempt to contract with Goddard just prior to the war.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] The Navy beat the Army to the punch and secured his services to build variable-thrust, liquid-fueled rocket engines for jet-assisted take-off (JATO) of aircraft.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] These rocket engines were the precursors to the larger throttlable rocket plane engines that helped launch the space age.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Astronaut Buzz Aldrin wrote that his father, Edwin Aldrin Sr.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] "was an early supporter of Robert Goddard." The elder Aldrin was a student of physics under Goddard at Clark, and worked with Lindbergh to obtain the help of the Guggenheims.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Buzz believed that if Goddard had received military support as Wernher von Braun's team had enjoyed in Germany, American rocket technology would have developed much more rapidly in World War II.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Before World War II there was a lack of vision and serious interest in the United States concerning the potential of rocketry, especially in Washington.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Although the Weather Bureau was interested beginning in 1929 in Goddard's rocket for atmospheric research, the Bureau could not secure governmental funding.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Between the World Wars, the Guggenheim Foundation was the main source of funding for Goddard's research.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard's liquid-fueled rocket was neglected by his country, according to aerospace historian Eugene Emme, but was noticed and advanced by other nations, especially the Germans.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Goddard showed remarkable prescience in 1923 in a letter to the Smithsonian.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] He knew that the Germans were very interested in rocketry and said he "would not be surprised if the research would become something in the nature of a race," and he wondered how soon the European "theorists" would begin to build rockets.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] In 1936, the U.S. military attaché in Berlin asked Charles Lindbergh to visit Germany and learn what he could of their progress in aviation.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Although the Luftwaffe showed him their factories and were open concerning their growing airpower, they were silent on the subject of rocketry.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] When Lindbergh told Goddard of this behavior, Goddard said, "Yes, they must have plans for the rocket.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Most of the U.S.'s largest universities were also slow to realize rocketry's potential.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] There were some exceptions: MIT was at least teaching basic rocketry, and Caltech had courses in rocketry and aerodynamics.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] While away in Roswell, Goddard was still head of the physics department at Clark University, and Clark allowed him to devote most of his time to rocket research.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Likewise, the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA) permitted astronomer Samuel Herrick to pursue research in space vehicle guidance and control, and shortly after the war to teach courses in spacecraft guidance and orbit determination.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Herrick began corresponding with Goddard in 1931 and asked if he should work in this new field, which he named astrodynamics.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p01] Herrick said that Goddard had the vision to advise and encourage him in his use of celestial mechanics "to anticipate the basic problem of space navigation." Herrick's work contributed substantially to America's readiness to control flight of Earth satellites and send men to the Moon and back.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] With new financial backing, Goddard eventually relocated to the Eden Valley Test Site in Roswell, New Mexico, in summer of 1930, where he worked with his team of technicians in near-isolation and relative secrecy for years.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He had consulted a meteorologist as to the best area to do his work, and Roswell seemed ideal.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Here they would not endanger anyone, would not be bothered by the curious and would experience a more moderate climate (which was also better for Goddard's health).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The locals valued personal privacy, knew Goddard desired his, and when travelers asked where Goddard's facilities were located, they would likely be misdirected.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] By September 1931, his rockets had the now familiar appearance of a smooth casing with tail-fins.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He began experimenting with gyroscopic guidance and made a flight test of such a system in April 1932.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] A gyroscope mounted on gimbals electrically controlled steering vanes in the exhaust, similar to the system used by the German V-2 over 10 years later.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Though the rocket crashed after a short ascent, the guidance system had worked, and Goddard considered the test a success.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] A temporary loss of funding from the Guggenheims, as a result of the depression, forced Goddard in spring of 1932 to return to his much-loathed professorial responsibilities at Clark University.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He remained at the university until the autumn of 1934, when funding resumed.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Because of the death of the senior Daniel Guggenheim, the management of funding was taken on by his son, Harry Guggenheim.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Upon his return to Roswell, he began work on his A series of rockets, 4 to 4.5 meters long, and powered by gasoline and liquid oxygen pressurized with nitrogen.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The gyroscopic control system was housed in the middle of the rocket, between the propellant tanks.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The A-4 used a simpler pendulum system for guidance, as the gyroscopic system was being repaired.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] It then turned to a nearly horizontal path, flew 13,000 feet and achieved a maximum speed of 550 miles per hour.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard was elated because the guidance system kept the rocket on a vertical path so well.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In 1936–1939, Goddard began work on the K and L series rockets, which were much more massive and designed to reach very high altitude.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The K series consisted of static bench tests of a more powerful engine, achieving a thrust of 624 lbs in February 1936.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] This work was plagued by trouble with chamber burn-through.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In 1923, Goddard had built a regeneratively cooled engine, which circulated liquid oxygen around the outside of the combustion chamber, but he deemed the idea too complicated.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] (This method is commonly used in modern engines.) He then used a curtain (film) cooling method that involved spraying excess gasoline, which evaporated around the inside wall of the combustion chamber, but this scheme did not work well, and the larger rockets failed.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] (With refining the method has been used successfully in modern engines.) Goddard returned to a smaller design, and his L-13 reached an altitude of 2.7 kilometers (1.7 mi; 8,900 ft), the highest of any of his rockets.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Weight was reduced by using thin-walled fuel tanks wound with high-tensile-strength wire.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard experimented with many of the features of today's large rockets, such as multiple combustion chambers and nozzles.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In November 1936, he flew the world's first rocket (L-7) with multiple chambers, hoping to increase thrust without increasing the size of a single chamber.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] It had four combustion chambers, reached a height of 200 feet, and corrected its vertical path using blast vanes until one chamber burned through.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] This flight demonstrated that a rocket with multiple combustion chambers could fly stably and be easily guided.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In July 1937 he replaced the guidance vanes with a movable tail section containing a single combustion chamber, as if on gimbals (thrust vectoring).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The flight was of low altitude, but a large disturbance, probably caused by a change in the wind velocity, was corrected back to vertical.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In an August test the flight path was corrected seven times by the movable tail and was captured on film by Mrs Goddard.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] From 1940 to 1941, Goddard worked on the P series of rockets, which used propellant turbopumps (also powered by gasoline and liquid oxygen).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The lightweight pumps produced higher propellant pressures, permitting a more powerful engine (greater thrust) and a lighter structure (lighter tanks and no pressurization tank), but two launches both ended in crashes after reaching an altitude of only a few hundred feet.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The turbopumps worked well, however, and Goddard was pleased.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] When Goddard mentioned the need for turbopumps, Harry Guggenheim suggested that he contact pump manufacturers to aid him.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] None were interested, as the development cost of these miniature pumps was prohibitive.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard's team was therefore left on its own and from September 1938 to June 1940 designed and tested the small turbopumps and gas generators to operate the turbines.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard was able to flight-test many of his rockets, but many resulted in what the uninitiated would call failures, usually resulting from engine malfunction or loss of control.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard did not consider them failures, however, because he felt that he always learned something from a test.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Most of his work involved static tests, which are a standard procedure today, before a flight test.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Jimmy Doolittle was introduced to the field of space science at an early point in its history.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He recalls in his autobiography, "I became interested in rocket development in the 1930s when I met Robert H.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] While with Shell Oil I worked with him on the development of a type of fuel. ...
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] " Harry Guggenheim and Charles Lindbergh arranged for (then Major) Doolittle to discuss with Goddard a special blend of gasoline.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Doolittle flew himself to Roswell in October 1938 and was given a tour of Goddard's shop and a "short course" in rocketry.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He then wrote a memo, including a rather detailed description of Goddard's rocket.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In closing he said, "interplanetary transportation is probably a dream of the very distant future, but with the moon only a quarter of a million miles away—who knows!" In July 1941, he wrote Goddard that he was still interested in his rocket propulsion research.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The Army was interested only in JATO at this point.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] However, Doolittle and Lindbergh were concerned about the state of rocketry in the US, and Doolittle remained in touch with Goddard.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Shortly after World War II, Doolittle spoke concerning Goddard to an American Rocket Society (ARS) conference at which a large number interested in rocketry attended.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He later stated that at that time "we [in the aeronautics field] had not given much credence to the tremendous potential of rocketry." In 1956, he was appointed chairman of the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics (NACA) because the previous chairman, Jerome C.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Hunsaker, thought Doolittle to be more sympathetic than other scientists and engineers to the rocket, which was increasing in importance as a scientific tool as well as a weapon.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Doolittle was instrumental in the successful transition of the NACA to the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) in 1958.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He was offered the position as first administrator of NASA, but he turned it down.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] As an instrument for reaching extreme altitudes, Goddard's rockets were not very successful; they did not achieve an altitude greater than 2.7 km in 1937, while a balloon sonde had already reached 35 km in 1921.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] By contrast, German rocket scientists had achieved an altitude of 2.4 km with the A-2 rocket in 1934, 8 km by 1939 with the A-5, and 176 km in 1942 with the A-4 (V-2) launched vertically, reaching the outer limits of the atmosphere and into space.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard's pace was slower than the Germans' because he did not have the resources they did.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He had built the necessary turbopumps and was on the verge of building larger, lighter, more reliable rockets to reach extreme altitudes carrying scientific instruments when World War II intervened and changed the path of American history.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He hoped to return to his experiments in Roswell after the war.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Although Goddard had brought his work in rocketry to the attention of the United States Army, between World Wars, he was rebuffed, since the Army largely failed to grasp the military application of large rockets and said there was no money for new experimental weapons.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] German military intelligence, by contrast, had paid attention to Goddard's work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The Goddards noticed that some mail had been opened, and some mailed reports had gone missing.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] An accredited military attaché to the US, Friedrich von Boetticher, sent a four-page report to the *Abwehr* in 1936, and the spy Gustav Guellich sent a mixture of facts and made-up information, claiming to have visited Roswell and witnessed a launch.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The *Abwehr* was very interested and responded with more questions about Goddard's work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Guellich's reports did include information about fuel mixtures and the important concept of fuel-curtain cooling, but thereafter the Germans received very little information about Goddard.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The Soviet Union had a spy (name still not declassified as of 2009) in the U.S.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In 1935, she gave them a report Goddard had written for the Navy in 1933.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] It contained results of tests and flights and suggestions for military uses of his rockets.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The Soviets considered this to be very valuable information.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] It provided few design details, but gave them the direction and knowledge about Goddard's progress.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Fischer, who had visited Goddard in Roswell earlier and gained his confidence, believed Goddard was doing valuable work and was able to convince the Bureau of Aeronautics in September 1941 that Goddard could build the JATO unit the Navy desired.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] While still in Roswell, and before the Navy contract took effect, Goddard began in September to apply his technology to build a variable-thrust engine to be attached to a PBY seaplane.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] By May 1942, he had a unit that could meet the Navy's requirements and be able to launch a heavily loaded aircraft from a short runway.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In February, he received part of a PBY with bullet holes apparently acquired in the Pearl Harbor attack.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In April, Fischer notified Goddard that the Navy wanted to do all its rocket work at the Engineering Experiment Station at Annapolis.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Esther, worried that a move to the climate of Maryland would cause Robert's health to deteriorate faster, objected.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] But the patriotic Goddard replied, "Esther, don't you know there's a war on?" Fischer also questioned the move, as Goddard could work just as well in Roswell.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard simply answered, "I was wondering when you would ask me." Fischer had wanted to offer him something bigger—a long range missile—but JATO was all he could manage, hoping for a greater project later.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] It was a case of a square peg in a round hole, according to a disappointed Goddard.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard and his team had already been in Annapolis a month and had tested his constant-thrust JATO engine when he received a Navy telegram, forwarded from Roswell, ordering him to Annapolis.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] By August, his engine was producing 800 lbs of thrust for 20 seconds, and Fischer was anxious to try it on a PBY.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] On the sixth test run, with all bugs worked out, the PBY, piloted by Fischer, was pushed into the air from the Severn River.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Fischer landed and prepared to launch again.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard had wanted to check the unit, but radio contact with the PBY had been lost.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] On the seventh try, the engine caught fire.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The plane was 150 feet up when flight was aborted.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Because Goddard had installed a safety feature at the last minute, there was no explosion and there were no deaths.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The problem's cause was traced to hasty installation and rough handling.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Cheaper, safer solid fuel JATO engines were eventually selected by the armed forces.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He regretfully resigned as professor of physics and expressed his deepest appreciation for all Atwood and the trustees had done for him and indirectly for the war effort.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In June he had gone to see a throat specialist in Baltimore, who recommended that he not talk at all, to give his throat a rest.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The station, under Lt Commander Robert Truax, was developing another JATO engine in 1942 that used hypergolic propellants, eliminating the need for an ignition system.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Chemist Ensign Ray Stiff had discovered in the literature in February that aniline and nitric acid burned fiercely immediately when mixed.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard's team built the pumps for the aniline fuel and the nitric acid oxidizer and participated in the static testing.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The Navy delivered the pumps to Reaction Motors (RMI) to use in developing a gas generator for the pump turbines.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard went to RMI to observe testing of the pump system and would eat lunch with the RMI engineers.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] (RMI was the first firm formed to build rocket engines and built engines for the Bell X-1 rocket plane and Viking (rocket).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He consulted with RMI from 1942 through 1945.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Though previously competitors, Goddard had a good working relationship with RMI, according to historian Frank H.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The Navy had Goddard build a pump system for Caltech's use with acid-aniline propellants.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The team built a 3000-lb thrust engine using a cluster of four 750-lb thrust motors.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] They also developed 750-lb engines for the Navy's Gorgon guided interceptor missile (experimental Project Gorgon).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard continued to develop the variable-thrust engine with gasoline and lox because of the hazards involved with the hypergolics.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Despite Goddard's efforts to convince the Navy that liquid-fueled rockets had greater potential, he said that the Navy had no interest in long-range missiles.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] However, the Navy asked him to perfect the throttleable JATO engine.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard made improvements to the engine, and in November it was demonstrated to the Navy and some officials from Washington.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Fischer invited the spectators to operate the controls; the engine blasted out over the Severn at full throttle with no hesitation, idled, and roared again at various thrust levels.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The test was perfect, exceeding the Navy's requirements.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The unit was able to be stopped and restarted, and it produced a medium thrust of 600 pounds for 15 seconds and a full thrust of 1,000 pounds for over 15 seconds.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] A Navy Commander commented that "It was like being Thor, playing with thunderbolts." Goddard had produced the essential propulsion control system of the rocket plane.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The Goddards celebrated by attending the Army-Navy football game and attending the Fischers' cocktail party.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] This engine was the basis of the Curtiss-Wright XLR25-CW-1 two-chamber, 15,000-pound variable-thrust engine that powered the Bell X-2 research rocket plane.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] After World War II, Goddard's team and some patents went to Curtiss-Wright Corporation.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] "Although his death in August 1945 prevented him from participating in the actual development of this engine, it was a direct descendent of his design." Clark University and the Guggenheim Foundation received the royalties from the use of the patents.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In September 1956, the X-2 was the first plane to reach 126,000 feet altitude and in its last flight exceeded Mach 3 (3.2) before losing control and crashing.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The X-2 program advanced technology in areas such as steel alloys and aerodynamics at high Mach numbers.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In the spring of 1945, Goddard saw a captured German V-2 ballistic missile, in the naval laboratory in Annapolis, Maryland, where he had been working under contract.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The unlaunched rocket had been captured by the US Army from the Mittelwerk factory in the Harz mountains in Germany and samples began to be shipped by Special Mission V-2 on 22 May 1945.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] After a thorough inspection, Goddard was convinced that the Germans had "stolen" his work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Though the design details were not exactly the same, the basic design of the V-2 was similar to one of Goddard's rockets.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The V-2, however, was technically far more advanced than the most successful of the rockets designed and tested by Goddard.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Oberth was a space flight theorist and had never built a rocket, but he tested small liquid propellant thrust chambers in 1929–30 which were not advances in the "state of the art".
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In 1922 Oberth asked Goddard for a copy of his 1919 paper and was sent one though Goddard was distrustful of the militaristic Germans.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Later, Oberth erroneously believed that Goddard lacked vision, was interested only in studying the atmosphere, and did not comprehend the future of rocketry for space exploration.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Nevertheless, in 1963, von Braun, reflecting on the history of rocketry, said of Goddard: "His rockets ... may have been rather crude by present-day standards, but they blazed the trail and incorporated many features used in our most modern rockets and space vehicles".
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He once recalled that "Goddard's experiments in liquid fuel saved us years of work, and enabled us to perfect the V-2 years before it would have been possible." After World War II von Braun reviewed Goddard's patents and believed they contained enough technical information to build a large missile.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The Germans had been watching Goddard's progress before the war and became convinced that large, liquid fuel rockets were feasible.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] General Walter Dornberger, head of the V-2 project, used the idea that they were in a race with the U.S. and that Goddard had "disappeared" (to work with the Navy) as a way to persuade Hitler to raise the priority of the V-2.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard avoided sharing details of his work with other scientists and preferred to work alone with his technicians.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Frank Malina, who was then studying rocketry at the California Institute of Technology, visited Goddard in August 1936.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard hesitated to discuss any of his research, other than that which had already been published in *Liquid-Propellant Rocket Development*.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Theodore von Kármán, Malina's mentor at the time, was unhappy with Goddard's attitude and later wrote, "Naturally we at Caltech wanted as much information as we could get from Goddard for our mutual benefit.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The trouble with secrecy is that one can easily go in the wrong direction and never know it." However, at an earlier point, von Kármán said that Malina was "highly enthusiastic" after his visit and that Caltech made changes to their liquid-propellant rocket, based on Goddard's work and patents.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Malina remembered his visit as friendly and that he saw all but a few components in Goddard's shop.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard's concerns about secrecy led to criticism for failure to cooperate with other scientists and engineers.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] His approach at that time was that independent development of his ideas without interference would bring quicker results even though he received less technical support.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] George Sutton, who became a rocket scientist working with von Braun's team in the late 1940s, said that he and his fellow workers had not heard of Goddard or his contributions and that they would have saved time if they had known the details of his work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] By 1939, von Kármán's GALCIT had received Army Air Corps funding to develop rockets to assist in aircraft take-off.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard learned of this in 1940, and openly expressed his displeasure at not being considered.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Malina could not understand why the Army did not arrange for an exchange of information between Goddard and Caltech since both were under government contract at the same time.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard did not think he could be of that much help to Caltech because they were designing rocket engines mainly with solid fuel, while he was using liquid fuel.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard was concerned with avoiding the public criticism and ridicule he had faced in the 1920s, which he believed had harmed his professional reputation.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He also lacked interest in discussions with people who had less understanding of rocketry than he did, feeling that his time was extremely constrained.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard's health was frequently poor, as a result of his earlier bout of tuberculosis, and he was uncertain about how long he had to live.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He felt, therefore, that he hadn't the time to spare arguing with other scientists and the press about his new field of research, or helping all the amateur rocketeers who wrote to him.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard spoke to professional groups, published articles and papers and patented his ideas; but while he discussed basic principles, he was unwilling to reveal the details of his designs until he had flown rockets to high altitudes and thus proven his theory.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He tended to avoid any mention of space flight, and spoke only of high-altitude research, since he believed that other scientists regarded the subject as unscientific.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] GALCIT saw Goddard's publicity problems and that the word "rocket" was "of such bad repute" that they used the word "jet" in the name of JPL and the related Aerojet Engineering Corporation.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Many authors writing about Goddard mention his secrecy, but neglect the reasons for it.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Much of his work was for the military and was classified.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] There were some in the U.S. before World War II that called for long-range rockets, and in 1939 Major James Randolph wrote a "provocative article" advocating a 3000-mile range missile.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] However, Goddard's tendency to secrecy was not absolute, nor was he totally uncooperative.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In 1945 GALCIT was building the WAC Corporal for the Army.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] But they were having trouble with their liquid propellant rocket engine's performance (timely, smooth ignition and explosions).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Frank Malina went to Annapolis in February and consulted with Goddard and Stiff, and they arrived at a solution to the problem (hypergolic propellant: nitric acid and aniline), which resulted in the successful launch of the high-altitude research rocket in October 1945.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] During the First and Second World Wars, Goddard offered his services, patents, and technology to the military, and made some significant contributions.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Just before the Second World War several young Army officers and a few higher-ranking ones believed Goddard's research was important but were unable to generate funds for his work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Toward the end of his life, Goddard, realizing he was no longer going to be able to make significant progress alone in his field, joined the American Rocket Society and became a director.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He made plans to work in the budding US aerospace industry (with Curtiss-Wright), taking most of his team with him.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] On June 21, 1924, Goddard married Esther Christine Kisk (March 31, 1901 – June 4, 1982), a secretary in Clark University's President's office, whom he had met in 1919.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] She became enthusiastic about rocketry and photographed some of his work as well as aided him in his experiments and paperwork, including accounting.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] They enjoyed going to the movies in Roswell and participated in community organizations such as the Rotary and the Woman's Club.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He painted the New Mexican scenery, sometimes with the artist Peter Hurd, and played the piano.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Esther said Robert participated in the community and readily accepted invitations to speak to church and service groups.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] After his death, she sorted out Goddard's papers, and secured 131 additional patents on his work.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] She also filmed some of the experiments that took place across the course of Goddard's research.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Concerning Goddard's religious views, he was raised as an Episcopalian, though he was not outwardly religious.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The Goddards were associated with the Episcopal church in Roswell, and he attended occasionally.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He once spoke to a young people's group on the relationship of science and religion.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard's serious bout with tuberculosis weakened his lungs, affecting his ability to work, and was one reason he liked to work alone, in order to avoid argument and confrontation with others and use his time fruitfully.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He labored with the prospect of a shorter than average life span.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] After arriving in Roswell, Goddard applied for life insurance, but when the company doctor examined him he said that Goddard belonged in a bed in Switzerland (where he could get the best care).
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard's health began to deteriorate further after moving to the humid climate of Maryland to work for the Navy.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He was diagnosed with throat cancer in 1945.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He continued to work, able to speak only in a whisper until surgery was required, and he died in August of that year in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] He was buried in Hope Cemetery in his home town of Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] Goddard received 214 patents for his work, of which 131 were awarded after his death.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The Guggenheim Foundation and Goddard's estate filed suit in 1951 against the U.S. government for prior infringement of three of Goddard's patents.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] In 1960, the parties settled the suit, and the U.S. armed forces and NASA paid out an award of $1 million: half of the award settlement went to his wife, Esther.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] At that time, it was the largest government settlement ever paid in a patent case.
[src:rocket/a-method-of-reaching-extreme-altitudes-p02] The settlement amount exceeded the total amount of all the funding that Goddard received for his work, throughout his entire career.
[src:rocket/acceleration] In physics, **acceleration** is a measure of how fast and in what direction an object's speed and direction of motion are changing.
[src:rocket/acceleration] It is defined as the rate of change of the velocity.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Like velocity, acceleration has a magnitude and a direction, making it a vector quantity.
[src:rocket/acceleration] The SI unit for acceleration is metre per second squared (m⋅s−2, m/s2).
[src:rocket/acceleration] The **tangential acceleration** of an object is the component of the **acceleration** which is in the same direction as the motion (or tangential velocity) of the object.
[src:rocket/acceleration] When the velocity of the object does not change direction, this is called **linear acceleration**.
[src:rocket/acceleration] **Deceleration** or **retardation**, on the other hand, is the component of the acceleration in the opposite (or antiparallel) direction to the tangential velocity.
[src:rocket/acceleration] **Radial acceleration** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motions) is the component of the acceleration that changes the direction of the object's velocity.
[src:rocket/acceleration] In Newtonian mechanics, the acceleration of a mass arises from forces acting on it, with its *net* acceleration being a result of the *net* force acting on it.
[src:rocket/acceleration] By Newton's second law, the magnitude of the *net* acceleration will be proportional to the magnitude of the *net* force acting on the object and inversely proportional to the mass of the object, while the direction of the *net* acceleration will be the same as the direction of the *net* force.
[src:rocket/acceleration] An object's average acceleration ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}$ over a period of time is its change in velocity, $\Delta \mathbf {v}$ , divided by the duration of the period, $\Delta t$ .
[src:rocket/acceleration] Mathematically, ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}={\frac {\Delta \mathbf {v} }{\Delta t}}.$ The average acceleration is the simplest way to measure acceleration, requiring only knowledge of the change in velocity and the change in time.
[src:rocket/acceleration] In a strict sense, the average acceleration is the only *true* acceleration one is able to directly measure without appealing to an empirical law, meaning that it is the most fundamental form of acceleration measurement.
[src:rocket/acceleration] The average acceleration is most often used to approximate the kinematics of an object by assuming that the velocity changes linearly with time.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Instantaneous acceleration is the limit of the average acceleration over an infinitesimal interval of time.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Acceleration has the dimensions of velocity (L/T) divided by time, i.e.
[src:rocket/acceleration] The SI unit of acceleration is the metre per second squared (m s−2); or "metre per second per second", as the velocity in metres per second changes by the acceleration value, every second.
[src:rocket/acceleration] An object moving in a circular motion—such as a satellite orbiting the Earth—is accelerating due to the change of direction of motion, although its speed may be constant.
[src:rocket/acceleration] In this case it is said to be undergoing *centripetal* (directed towards the center) acceleration.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Proper acceleration, the acceleration of a body relative to a free-fall condition, is measured by an instrument called an accelerometer.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Newton's second law is normally applied in an inertial reference frame.
[src:rocket/acceleration] In a reference frame accelerating with acceleration a (in one dimension), Newton's laws can still be used by introducing an inertial force (fictitious force) $F=-ma$ on a mass m , opposite the acceleration of the frame.
[src:rocket/acceleration] This accounts for the tendency of the mass to maintain its inertial motion—to stay "as is," at rest or moving at constant velocity—while the frame accelerates.
[src:rocket/acceleration] One example is that a person in an elevator feels heavier or lighter as the elevator accelerates or decelerates.
[src:rocket/acceleration] If m is known, measurement of the supporting force on the mass can be used to infer the acceleration; this is the principle of a mechanical accelerometer.
[src:rocket/acceleration] In general relativity, gravity and inertial acceleration may be locally indistinguishable (see General relativity).
[src:rocket/acceleration] As speeds approach the speed of light, relativistic effects become increasingly large.
[src:rocket/acceleration] When a vehicle starts from a standstill (zero velocity, in an inertial frame of reference) and travels in a straight line at increasing speeds, it is accelerating in the direction of travel.
[src:rocket/acceleration] If the vehicle turns, an acceleration occurs toward the new direction and changes its motion vector.
[src:rocket/acceleration] The component of acceleration of the vehicle in the direction of its velocity is called a **linear acceleration** or **tangential acceleration**, its effect being the passengers on board experience as a fictitious force pushing them back into or away from their seats.
[src:rocket/acceleration] When changing direction, the component of the acceleration perpendicular to the velocity is called **radial** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motion), the reaction to which the passengers experience as a centrifugal force (another fictitious force).
[src:rocket/acceleration] If the speed of the vehicle decreases, this is an acceleration in the opposite direction of the velocity vector, sometimes called **deceleration** or **retardation**, and passengers experience the reaction to deceleration as an inertial force pushing them forward.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Such deceleration is often achieved by retrorocket burning in spacecraft.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Both acceleration and deceleration are treated the same, as they are both changes in velocity.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Each of these accelerations (tangential, radial, deceleration) is felt by passengers until their relative (differential) velocity is neutralised in reference to the acceleration due to change in speed.
[src:rocket/acceleration] where **u**n is the unit (inward) normal vector to the particle's trajectory (also called *the principal normal*), and **r** is its instantaneous radius of curvature based upon the osculating circle at time t.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Geometrical analysis of three-dimensional space curves, which explains tangent, (principal) normal and binormal, is described by the Frenet–Serret formulas.
[src:rocket/acceleration] A frequently cited example of uniform acceleration is that of an object in free fall in a uniform gravitational field.
[src:rocket/acceleration] The acceleration of a falling body in the absence of resistances to motion is dependent only on the gravitational field strength g (also called *acceleration due to gravity*).
[src:rocket/acceleration] In particular, the motion can be resolved into two orthogonal parts, one of constant velocity and the other according to the above equations.
[src:rocket/acceleration] As Galileo showed, the net result is parabolic motion, which describes, e.g., the trajectory of a projectile in vacuum near the surface of Earth.
[src:rocket/acceleration] , always points radially from the origin.
[src:rocket/acceleration] , not parallel to the radial motion but offset by the angular and Coriolis accelerations, nor tangent to the path but offset by the centripetal and radial accelerations.
[src:rocket/acceleration] plane in a point of an arbitrary curve in any higher dimension.
[src:rocket/acceleration] In uniform circular motion, that is moving with constant *speed* along a circular path, a particle experiences an acceleration resulting from the change of the direction of the velocity vector, while its magnitude remains constant.
[src:rocket/acceleration] The derivative of the location of a point on a curve with respect to time, i.e. its velocity, turns out to be always exactly tangential to the curve, respectively orthogonal to the radius in this point.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Since in uniform motion the velocity in the tangential direction does not change, the acceleration must be in radial direction, pointing to the center of the circle.
[src:rocket/acceleration] This acceleration constantly changes the direction of the velocity to be tangent in the neighbouring point, thereby rotating the velocity vector along the circle.
[src:rocket/acceleration] This acceleration and the mass of the particle determine the necessary centripetal force, directed *toward* the centre of the circle, as the net force acting on this particle to keep it in this uniform circular motion.
[src:rocket/acceleration] The so-called 'centrifugal force', appearing to act outward on the body, is a so-called pseudo force experienced in the frame of reference of the body in circular motion, due to the body's linear momentum, a vector tangent to the circle of motion.
[src:rocket/acceleration] The tangential component is given by the angular acceleration $\alpha$ , i.e., the rate of change $\alpha ={\dot {\omega }}$ of the angular speed $\omega$ times the radius r .
[src:rocket/acceleration] The sign of the tangential component of the acceleration is determined by the sign of the angular acceleration ( $\alpha$ ), and the tangent is always directed at right angles to the radius vector.
[src:rocket/acceleration] In multi-dimensional Cartesian coordinate systems, acceleration is broken up into components that correspond with each dimensional axis of the coordinate system.
[src:rocket/acceleration] The special theory of relativity describes the behaviour of objects travelling relative to other objects at speeds approaching that of light in vacuum.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Newtonian mechanics is exactly revealed to be an approximation to reality, valid to great accuracy at lower speeds.
[src:rocket/acceleration] As the relevant speeds increase toward the speed of light, acceleration no longer follows classical equations.
[src:rocket/acceleration] As speeds approach that of light, the acceleration produced by a given force decreases, becoming infinitesimally small as light speed is approached; an object with mass can approach this speed asymptotically, but never reach it.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Unless the state of motion of an object is known, it is impossible to distinguish whether an observed force is due to gravity or to acceleration—gravity and inertial acceleration have identical effects.
[src:rocket/acceleration] Albert Einstein called this the equivalence principle, and said that only observers who feel no force at all—including the force of gravity—are justified in concluding that they are not accelerating.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In fluid dynamics, **drag**, sometimes referred to as **fluid resistance**, and also known as **viscous force**, is a force acting opposite to the direction of motion of any object moving with respect to a surrounding fluid.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] This can exist between two fluid layers, or between a fluid and a solid surface.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Drag forces tend to decrease fluid velocity relative to the solid object in the fluid's path.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Unlike other resistive forces, drag force depends on velocity.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Drag force is proportional to the relative velocity for low-speed flow and is proportional to the velocity squared for high-speed flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] This distinction between low and high-speed flow is measured by the Reynolds number.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] There are many distinct types of drag caused by different physical interactions between the object and fluid.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Last, in aerodynamics the term "parasitic drag" is often used.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Parasitic drag is the sum of form drag and skin friction drag and is entirely negative to an aircraft, in contrast with lift-induced drag which is a consequence of generating lift.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The effect of streamlining on the relative proportions of skin friction and form drag is shown in the table at right for an airfoil, which is a streamlined body, and a cylinder, which is a bluff body.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Also shown is a flat plate in two different orientations, illustrating the effect of orientation on the relative proportions of skin friction and form drag, and showing the pressure difference between front and back.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] A body is known as bluff or blunt when the source of drag is dominated by pressure forces, and streamlined if the drag is dominated by viscous forces.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For example, road vehicles are bluff bodies.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For aircraft, pressure and friction drag are included in the definition of parasitic drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Parasite drag is often expressed in terms of a hypothetical.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] With other parameters remaining the same, as the lift generated by a body increases, so does the lift-induced drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] This means that as the wing's angle of attack increases (up to a maximum called the stalling angle), the lift coefficient also increases, and so too does the lift-induced drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] At the onset of stall, lift is abruptly decreased, as is lift-induced drag, but viscous pressure drag, a component of parasite drag, increases due to the formation of turbulent unattached flow in the wake behind the body.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For an aircraft at low speed, induced drag tends to be relatively greater than parasitic drag because a high angle of attack is required to maintain lift, increasing induced drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] As speed increases, the angle of attack is reduced and the induced drag decreases.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Parasitic drag, however, increases because the fluid is flowing more quickly around protruding objects increasing friction or drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] At even higher speeds (transonic), wave drag enters the picture.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Each of these forms of drag changes in proportion to the others based on speed.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The combined overall drag curve therefore shows a minimum at some airspeed - an aircraft flying at this speed will be at or close to its optimal efficiency.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Pilots will use this speed to maximize endurance (minimum fuel consumption), or maximize gliding range in the event of an engine failure.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The equivalent parasite area is the area which a flat plate perpendicular to the flow would have to match the parasite drag of an aircraft.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] It is a measure used when comparing the drag of different aircraft.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For example, the Douglas DC-3 has an equivalent parasite area of 2.20 m2 (23.7 ft2) and the McDonnell Douglas DC-9, with 30 years of advancement in aircraft design, an area of 1.91 m2 (20.6 ft2) although it carried five times as many passengers.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Drag depends on the properties of the fluid and on the size, shape, and speed of the object.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The graph to the right shows how $C_{\rm {D}}$ varies with $\mathrm {Re}$ for the case of a sphere.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Since the power needed to overcome the drag force is the product of the force times speed, the power needed to overcome drag will vary as the square of the speed at low Reynolds numbers, and as the cube of the speed at high numbers.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] It can be demonstrated that drag force can be expressed as a function of a dimensionless number, which is dimensionally identical to the Bejan number.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Consequently, drag force and drag coefficient can be a function of Bejan number.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] As mentioned, the drag equation with a constant drag coefficient gives the force moving through a fluid at a relatively large velocity, i.e. high Reynolds number, Re > ~1000.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The reference area *A* is often the orthographic projection of the object, or the *frontal area,* on a plane perpendicular to the direction of motion.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For objects with a simple shape, such as a sphere, this is the cross sectional area.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Sometimes a body is a composite of different parts, each with a different reference area (drag coefficient corresponding to each of those different areas must be determined).
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In the case of a **wing**, the reference areas are the same, and the drag force is in the same ratio as the lift force.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Therefore, the reference for a wing is often the lifting area, sometimes referred to as "wing area" rather than the frontal area.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For an object with a smooth surface, and non-fixed separation points (like a sphere or circular cylinder), the drag coefficient may vary with Reynolds number *Re*, up to extremely high values (*Re* of the order 107).
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For an object with well-defined fixed separation points, like a circular disk with its plane normal to the flow direction, the drag coefficient is constant for *Re* > 3,500.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The further the drag coefficient *Cd* is, in general, a function of the orientation of the flow with respect to the object (apart from symmetrical objects like a sphere).
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For example, a car cruising on a highway at 50 mph (80 km/h) may require only 10 horsepower (7.5 kW) to overcome aerodynamic drag, but that same car at 100 mph (160 km/h) requires 80 hp (60 kW).
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] With a doubling of speeds, the drag/force quadruples per the formula.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Exerting 4 times the force over a fixed distance produces 4 times as much work.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] At twice the speed, the work (resulting in displacement over a fixed distance) is done twice as fast.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Since power is the rate of doing work, 4 times the work done in half the time requires 8 times the power.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Where $v_{w}$ is the wind speed and $v_{o}$ is the object speed (both relative to ground).
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The hyperbolic cotangent also has a limit value of one, for large time *t*.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Velocity asymptotically tends to the terminal velocity *vt*, strictly from above *vt*.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For objects of water-like density (raindrops, hail, live objects—mammals, birds, insects, etc.) falling in air near Earth's surface at sea level, the terminal velocity is roughly equal to $v_{t}=90{\sqrt {d}},\,$ with *d* in metres and *vt* in m/s.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Terminal velocity for very small objects (pollen, etc.) at low Reynolds numbers is determined by Stokes law.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In short, terminal velocity is higher for larger creatures, and thus potentially more deadly.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] A creature such as a mouse falling at its terminal velocity is much more likely to survive impact with the ground than a human falling at its terminal velocity.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The equation for **viscous resistance** or **linear drag** is appropriate for objects or particles moving through a fluid at relatively slow speeds (assuming there is no turbulence).
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Purely laminar flow only exists up to Re = 0.1 under this definition.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In this case, the force of drag is approximately proportional to velocity.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The velocity asymptotically approaches the terminal velocity $v_{t}={\frac {(\rho -\rho _{0})Vg}{b}}$ .
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For a given b , denser objects fall more quickly.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For the special case of small spherical objects moving slowly through a viscous fluid (and thus at small Reynolds number), George Gabriel Stokes derived an expression for the drag constant: $b=6\pi \eta r\,$ where r is the Stokes radius of the particle, and $\eta$ is the fluid viscosity.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For example, consider a small sphere with radius r = 0.5 micrometre (diameter = 1.0 μm) moving through water at a velocity v of 10 μm/s.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Using 10−3 Pa·s as the dynamic viscosity of water in SI units, we find a drag force of 0.09 pN.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] This is about the drag force that a bacterium experiences as it swims through water.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] For Reynolds numbers less than 1, Stokes' law applies and the drag coefficient approaches ${\frac {24}{Re}}$ .
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In aerodynamics, **aerodynamic drag**, also known as **air resistance**, is the fluid drag force that acts on any moving solid body in the direction of the air's freestream flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Alternatively, calculated from the flow field perspective (far-field approach), the drag force results from three natural phenomena: shock waves, vortex sheet, and viscosity.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] When the airplane produces lift, another drag component results.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Induced drag, symbolized $D_{i}$ , is due to a modification of the pressure distribution due to the trailing vortex system that accompanies the lift production.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] An alternative perspective on lift and drag is gained from considering the change of momentum of the airflow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The wing intercepts the airflow and forces the flow to move downward.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] This results in an equal and opposite force acting upward on the wing which is the lift force.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The change of momentum of the airflow downward results in a reduction of the rearward momentum of the flow which is the result of a force acting forward on the airflow and applied by the wing to the air flow; an equal but opposite force acts on the wing rearward which is the induced drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Another drag component, namely wave drag, $D_{w}$ , results from shock waves in transonic and supersonic flight speeds.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The shock waves induce changes in the boundary layer and pressure distribution over the body surface.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Therefore, there are three ways of categorizing drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The pressure distribution acting on a body's surface *exerts* normal forces on the body.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Those forces can be added together and the component of that force that acts downstream represents the drag force, $D_{pr}$ .
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The nature of these normal forces combines shock wave effects, vortex system generation effects, and wake viscous mechanisms.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Viscosity of the fluid has a major effect on drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In the absence of viscosity, the pressure forces acting to hinder the vehicle are canceled by a pressure force further aft that acts to push the vehicle forward; this is called pressure recovery and the result is that the drag is zero.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] That is to say, the work the body does on the airflow is reversible and is recovered as there are no frictional effects to convert the flow energy into heat.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Pressure recovery acts even in the case of viscous flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Viscosity, however results in pressure drag and it is the dominant component of drag in the case of vehicles with regions of separated flow, in which the pressure recovery is infective.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The friction drag force, which is a tangential force on the aircraft surface, depends substantially on boundary layer configuration and viscosity.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The net friction drag, $D_{f}$ , is calculated as the downstream projection of the viscous forces evaluated over the body's surface.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The sum of friction drag and pressure (form) drag is called viscous drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] This drag component is due to viscosity.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The idea that a moving body passing through air or another fluid encounters resistance had been known since the time of Aristotle.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] According to Mervyn O'Gorman, this was named "drag" by Archibald Reith Low.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Louis Charles Breguet's paper of 1922 began efforts to reduce drag by streamlining.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Breguet went on to put his ideas into practice by designing several record-breaking aircraft in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Ludwig Prandtl's boundary layer theory in the 1920s provided the impetus to minimise skin friction.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] A further major call for streamlining was made by Sir Melvill Jones who provided the theoretical concepts to demonstrate emphatically the importance of streamlining in aircraft design.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In 1929 his paper 'The Streamline Airplane' presented to the Royal Aeronautical Society was seminal.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] He proposed an ideal aircraft that would have minimal drag which led to the concepts of a 'clean' monoplane and retractable undercarriage.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The aspect of Jones's paper that most shocked the designers of the time was his plot of the horse power required versus velocity, for an actual and an ideal plane.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] By looking at a data point for a given aircraft and extrapolating it horizontally to the ideal curve, the velocity gain for the same power can be seen.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] When Jones finished his presentation, a member of the audience described the results as being of the same level of importance as the Carnot cycle in thermodynamics.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The interaction of parasitic and induced drag *vs.* airspeed can be plotted as a characteristic curve, illustrated here.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In aviation, this is often referred to as the *power curve*, and is important to pilots because it shows that, below a certain airspeed, maintaining airspeed counterintuitively requires *more* thrust as speed decreases, rather than less.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The consequences of being "behind the curve" in flight are important and are taught as part of pilot training.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] At the subsonic airspeeds where the "U" shape of this curve is significant, wave drag has not yet become a factor, and so it is not shown in the curve.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Wave drag, sometimes referred to as compressibility drag, is drag that is created when a body moves in a compressible fluid and at the speed that is close to the speed of sound in that fluid.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In aerodynamics, wave drag consists of multiple components depending on the speed regime of the flight.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In transonic flight, wave drag is the result of the formation of shockwaves in the fluid, formed when local areas of supersonic (Mach number greater than 1.0) flow are created.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In practice, supersonic flow occurs on bodies traveling well below the speed of sound, as the local speed of air increases as it accelerates over the body to speeds above Mach 1.0.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] However, full supersonic flow over the vehicle will not develop until well past Mach 1.0.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Aircraft flying at transonic speed often incur wave drag through the normal course of operation.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In transonic flight, wave drag is commonly referred to as **transonic compressibility drag**.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Transonic compressibility drag increases significantly as the speed of flight increases towards Mach 1.0, dominating other forms of drag at those speeds.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In supersonic flight (Mach numbers greater than 1.0), **wave drag** is the result of shockwaves present in the fluid and attached to the body, typically **oblique shockwaves** formed at the leading and trailing edges of the body.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In highly supersonic flows, or in bodies with turning angles sufficiently large, **unattached shockwaves**, or **bow waves** will instead form.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Additionally, local areas of transonic flow behind the initial shockwave may occur at lower supersonic speeds, and can lead to the development of additional, smaller shockwaves present on the surfaces of other lifting bodies, similar to those found in transonic flows.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In supersonic flow regimes, **wave drag** is commonly separated into two components, **supersonic lift-dependent wave drag** and **supersonic volume-dependent wave drag**.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The closed form solution for the minimum wave drag of a body of revolution with a fixed length was found by Sears and Haack, and is known as the **Sears-Haack Distribution**.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Similarly, for a fixed volume, the shape for minimum wave drag is the **Von Karman Ogive**.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The Busemann biplane theoretical concept is not subject to wave drag when operated at its design speed, but is incapable of generating lift in this condition.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In 1752 d'Alembert proved that potential flow, the 18th century state-of-the-art inviscid flow theory amenable to mathematical solutions, resulted in the prediction of zero drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] This was in contradiction with experimental evidence, and became known as d'Alembert's paradox.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In the 19th century the Navier–Stokes equations for the description of viscous flow were developed by Saint-Venant, Navier, and Stokes.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Stokes derived the drag around a sphere at very low Reynolds numbers, the result of which is called Stokes' law.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] In the limit of high Reynolds numbers, the Navier–Stokes equations approach the inviscid Euler equations, of which the potential-flow solutions considered by d'Alembert are solutions.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] However, all experiments at high Reynolds numbers showed there is drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] Attempts to construct inviscid steady flow solutions to the Euler equations, other than the potential flow solutions, did not result in realistic results.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The notion of boundary layers—introduced by Prandtl in 1904, founded on both theory and experiments—explained the causes of drag at high Reynolds numbers.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic-drag] The boundary layer is the thin layer of fluid close to the object's boundary, where viscous effects remain important even when the viscosity is very small (or equivalently the Reynolds number is very large).
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:rocket/aerodynamic] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] "Aeronautical engineering" was the original term for the field.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] As flight technology advanced to include vehicles operating in outer space, the broader term "aerospace engineering" has come into use.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Aerospace engineering, particularly the astronautics branch, is often colloquially referred to as "rocket science".
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Flight vehicles are subjected to demanding conditions such as those caused by changes in atmospheric pressure and temperature, with structural loads applied upon vehicle components.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Consequently, they are usually the products of various technological and engineering disciplines including aerodynamics, air propulsion, avionics, materials science, structural analysis and manufacturing.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The interaction between these technologies is known as aerospace engineering.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Because of the complexity and number of disciplines involved, aerospace engineering is carried out by teams of engineers, each having their own specialized area of expertise.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The origin of aerospace engineering can be traced back to the aviation pioneers around the late 19th to early 20th centuries, although the work of Sir George Cayley dates from the last decade of the 18th to the mid-19th century.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] One of the most important people in the history of aeronautics and a pioneer in aeronautical engineering, Cayley is credited as the first person to separate the forces of lift and drag, which affect any atmospheric flight vehicle.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Early knowledge of aeronautical engineering was largely empirical, with some concepts and skills imported from other branches of engineering.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Some key elements, like fluid dynamics, were understood by 18th-century scientists.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] In December 1903, the Wright Brothers performed the first sustained, controlled flight of a powered, heavier-than-air aircraft, lasting 12 seconds.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The 1910s saw the development of aeronautical engineering through the design of World War I military aircraft.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] In 1914, Robert Goddard was granted two U.S. patents for rockets using solid fuel, liquid fuel, multiple propellant charges, and multi-stage designs.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] This would set the stage for future applications in multi-stage propulsion systems for outer space.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Congress established the first aeronautical research administration, known as the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics, or NACA.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] It was the first government-sponsored organization to support aviation research.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Though intended as an advisory board upon inception, the Langley Aeronautical Laboratory became its first sponsored research and testing facility in 1920.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The organization would later be redefined as NASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Between World Wars I and II, great leaps were made in the field, accelerated by the advent of mainstream civil aviation.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Notable airplanes of this era include the Curtiss JN 4, Farman F.60 Goliath, and Fokker Trimotor.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Notable military airplanes of this period include the Mitsubishi A6M Zero, Supermarine Spitfire and Messerschmitt Bf 109 from Japan, United Kingdom, and Germany respectively.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] A significant development came with the first operational Jet engine-powered airplane, the Messerschmitt Me 262 which entered service in 1944 towards the end of the Second World War.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The first definition of aerospace engineering appeared in February 1958, considering the Earth's atmosphere and outer space as a single realm, thereby encompassing both aircraft (*aero*) and spacecraft (*space*) under the newly coined term *aerospace*.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] In response to the USSR launching the first satellite, Sputnik, into space on October 4, 1957, U.S. aerospace engineers launched the first American satellite on January 31, 1958.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The National Aeronautics and Space Administration was founded in 1958 after the Sputnik crisis.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] In 1969, Apollo 11, the first human space mission to land on the Moon, took place.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] It saw three astronauts enter orbit around the Moon, with two, Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin, visiting the lunar surface.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The third astronaut, Michael Collins, stayed in orbit to rendezvous with Armstrong and Aldrin after their visit.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] An important innovation came on January 30, 1970, when the Boeing 747 made its first commercial flight from New York to London.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] This aircraft made history and became known as the "Jumbo Jet" or "Queen of the Skies" due to its ability to hold up to 480 passengers.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Another significant development came in 1976, with the development of the first passenger supersonic aircraft, the Concorde.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The development of this aircraft was agreed upon by the French and British on November 29, 1962.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] On December 21, 1988, the Antonov An-225 *Mriya* cargo aircraft commenced its first flight.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] It holds the records for the world's heaviest aircraft, heaviest airlifted cargo, and longest airlifted cargo of any aircraft in operational service.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] On October 25, 2007, the Airbus A380 made its maiden commercial flight from Singapore to Sydney, Australia.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] This aircraft was the first passenger plane to surpass the Boeing 747 in terms of passenger capacity, with a maximum of 853.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Though development of this aircraft began in 1988 as a competitor to the 747, the A380 made its first test flight in April 2005.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The basis of most of these elements lies in theoretical physics, such as fluid dynamics for aerodynamics or the equations of motion for flight dynamics.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] There is also a large empirical component.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Historically, this empirical component was derived from testing of scale models and prototypes, either in wind tunnels or in the free atmosphere.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] More recently, advances in computing have enabled the use of computational fluid dynamics to simulate the behavior of the fluid, reducing time and expense spent on wind-tunnel testing.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Those studying hydrodynamics or hydroacoustics often obtain degrees in aerospace engineering.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Aerospace engineering may be studied at the advanced diploma, bachelor's, master's, and Ph.D. levels in aerospace engineering departments at many universities, and in mechanical engineering departments at others.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] A few departments offer degrees in space-focused astronautical engineering.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Some institutions differentiate between aeronautical and astronautical engineering.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Graduate degrees are offered in advanced or specialty areas for the aerospace industry.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] A background in chemistry, physics, computer science and mathematics is important for students pursuing an aerospace engineering degree.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The term "rocket scientist" is sometimes used to describe a person of great intelligence since rocket science is seen as a practice requiring great mental ability, especially technically and mathematically.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The term is used ironically in the expression "It's not rocket science" to indicate that a task is simple.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] Strictly speaking, the use of "science" in "rocket science" is a misnomer since science is about understanding the origins, nature, and behavior of the universe; engineering is about using scientific and engineering principles to solve problems and develop new technology.
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] The more etymologically correct version of this phrase would be "rocket engineer".
[src:rocket/aerospace-engineering] However, "science" and "engineering" are often misused as synonyms.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] A **rocket** (from Italian: *rocchetto*, lit.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] ''bobbin/spool'', and so named for its shape) is an elongated flying vehicle that uses a rocket engine to accelerate without using any surrounding air.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] A rocket engine produces thrust by reaction to exhaust expelled at high speed.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Unlike jet engines, rockets are fuelled entirely by propellant which they carry, without the need for oxygen from air; consequently a rocket can fly in the vacuum of space, indeed rocket engines operate more efficiently outside the atmosphere.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Multistage rockets are capable of attaining escape velocity from Earth and therefore can achieve unlimited maximum altitude.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Compared with airbreathing engines, rockets are lightweight and powerful and capable of generating large accelerations.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] To control their flight, rockets may use momentum, airfoils, auxiliary reaction engines, gimballed thrust, momentum wheels, deflection of the exhaust stream, propellant flow, and spin, or may simply fly in a ballistic trajectory under the influence of gravity.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rockets for military and recreational uses date back to at least 13th-century China.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Significant scientific, interplanetary and industrial use did not occur until the 20th century, when rocketry was the enabling technology for the Space Age, including setting foot on the Moon.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rockets are now used for fireworks, missiles and other weaponry, ejection seats, launch vehicles for artificial satellites, human spaceflight, and space exploration.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Chemical rockets are the most common type of high-power rocket, typically creating a high-speed exhaust by the combustion of fuel with an oxidizer.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Chemical rockets store a large amount of energy in an easily released form, and the consequences of accidents can be severe.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The term "rocket" is also used for small fireworks, which are the subject of article rocket (firework).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Gunpowder-powered rockets evolved in medieval China under the Song dynasty by the 13th century.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] They also developed an early form of multiple rocket launcher during this time.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The Mongols adopted Chinese rocket technology and the invention spread via the Mongol invasions to the Middle East and to Europe in the mid-13th century.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] According to Joseph Needham, the Song navy used rockets in a military exercise dated to 1245.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Internal-combustion rocket propulsion is mentioned in a reference to 1264, recording that the "ground-rat", a type of firework, had frightened the Empress-Mother Gongsheng at a feast held in her honor by her son the Emperor Lizong.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Subsequently, rockets are included in the military treatise *Huolongjing*, also known as the Fire Drake Manual, written by the Chinese artillery officer Jiao Yu in the mid-14th century.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This text mentions the first known multistage rocket, the 'fire-dragon issuing from the water' (Huo long chu shui), thought to have been used by the Chinese navy.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Medieval and early modern rockets were used militarily as incendiary weapons in sieges.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Between 1270 and 1280, Hasan al-Rammah wrote *al-furusiyyah wa al-manasib al-harbiyya* (*The Book of Military Horsemanship and Ingenious War Devices*), which included 107 gunpowder recipes, 22 of them for rockets.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In Europe, Roger Bacon mentioned firecrackers made in various parts of the world in the *Opus Majus* of 1267.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Between 1280 and 1300, the Liber Ignium (*Book of Fire*) gave instructions for constructing devices that are similar to firecrackers based on second-hand accounts.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Konrad Kyeser described rockets in his military treatise *Bellifortis* around 1405.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Giovanni Fontana, a Paduan engineer in 1420, created rocket-propelled animal figures.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The name "rocket" comes from the Italian *rocchetta*, meaning "bobbin" or "little spindle", given due to the similarity in shape to the bobbin or spool used to hold the thread from a spinning wheel.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Leonhard Fronsperger and Conrad Haas adopted the Italian term into German in the mid-16th century; "rocket" appears in English by the early 17th century.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] *Artis Magnae Artilleriae pars prima*, an important early modern work on rocket artillery, by Casimir Siemienowicz, was first printed in Amsterdam in 1650.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The Mysorean rockets were the first successful iron-cased rockets, developed in the late 18th century in the Kingdom of Mysore (part of present-day India) under the rule of Hyder Ali.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The Congreve rocket was a British weapon designed and developed by Sir William Congreve in 1804.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This rocket was based directly on the Mysorean rockets, used compressed powder and was fielded in the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] It was Congreve rockets to which Francis Scott Key was referring, when he wrote of the "rockets' red glare" while held captive on a British ship that was laying siege to Fort McHenry in 1814.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Together, the Mysorean and British innovations increased the effective range of military rockets from 100 to 2,000 yards (91 to 1,829 m).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The first mathematical treatment of the dynamics of rocket propulsion is due to William Moore (1813).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In 1814, Congreve published a book in which he discussed the use of multiple rocket launching apparatus.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In 1815 Alexander Dmitrievich Zasyadko constructed rocket-launching platforms, which allowed rockets to be fired in salvos (6 rockets at a time), and gun-laying devices.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] William Hale in 1844 greatly increased the accuracy of rocket artillery.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Edward Mounier Boxer further improved the Congreve rocket in 1865.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] William Leitch first proposed the concept of using rockets to enable human spaceflight in 1861.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Leitch's rocket spaceflight description was first provided in his 1861 essay "A Journey Through Space".
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The essay was published in a journal in Edinburgh that year before being included in his book *God's Glory in the Heavens* (1862).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Konstantin Tsiolkovsky later (in 1903) also conceived this idea, and extensively developed a body of theory that has provided the foundation for subsequent spaceflight development.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The British Royal Flying Corps designed a guided rocket during World War I.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Archibald Low stated "...in 1917 the Experimental Works designed an electrically steered rocket… Rocket experiments were conducted under my own patents with the help of Cdr.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Brock." The patent "Improvements in Rockets" was raised in July 1918 but not published until February 1923 for security reasons.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Firing and guidance controls could be either wire or wireless.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The propulsion and guidance rocket eflux emerged from the deflecting cowl at the nose.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In 1920, Professor Robert Goddard of Clark University published proposed improvements to rocket technology in *A Method of Reaching Extreme Altitudes*.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In 1923, Hermann Oberth (1894–1989) published *Die Rakete zu den Planetenräumen* (*The Rocket into Planetary Space*).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Modern rockets originated in 1926 when Goddard attached a supersonic (de Laval) nozzle to a high pressure combustion chamber.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] These nozzles turn the hot gas from the combustion chamber into a cooler, hypersonic, highly directed jet of gas, more than doubling the thrust and raising the engine efficiency from 2% to 64%.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] His use of liquid propellants instead of gunpowder greatly lowered the weight and increased the effectiveness of rockets.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In 1921, the Soviet research and development laboratory Gas Dynamics Laboratory began developing solid-propellant rockets, which resulted in the first launch in 1928, which flew for approximately 1,300 metres.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] These rockets were used in 1931 for the world's first successful use of rockets for jet-assisted takeoff of aircraft and became the prototypes for the Katyusha rocket launcher, which were used during World War II.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In 1929, Fritz Lang's German science fiction film *Woman in the Moon* was released.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] It showcased the use of a multi-stage rocket, and also pioneered the concept of a rocket launch pad (a rocket standing upright against a tall building before launch having been slowly rolled into place) and the rocket-launch countdown clock.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] *The Guardian* film critic Stephen Armstrong states Lang "created the rocket industry".
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Lang was inspired by the 1923 book *The Rocket into Interplanetary Space* by Hermann Oberth, who became the film's scientific adviser and later an important figure in the team that developed the V-2 rocket.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The film was thought to be so realistic that it was banned by the Nazis when they came to power for fear it would reveal secrets about the V-2 rockets.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In 1943 production of the V-2 rocket began in Germany.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] It was designed by the Peenemünde Army Research Center with Wernher von Braun serving as the technical director.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The V-2 became the first artificial object to travel into space by crossing the Kármán line with the vertical launch of MW 18014 on 20 June 1944.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Doug Millard, space historian and curator of space technology at the Science Museum, London, where a V-2 is exhibited in the main exhibition hall, states: "The V-2 was a quantum leap of technological change.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] We got to the Moon using V-2 technology but this was technology that was developed with massive resources, including some particularly grim ones.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The V-2 programme was hugely expensive in terms of lives, with the Nazis using slave labour to manufacture these rockets".
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In parallel with the German guided-missile programme, rockets were also used on aircraft, either for assisting horizontal take-off (RATO), vertical take-off (Bachem Ba 349 "Natter") or for powering them (Me 163, see list of World War II guided missiles of Germany).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The Allies' rocket programs were less technological, relying mostly on unguided missiles like the Soviet Katyusha rocket in the artillery role, and the American anti tank bazooka projectile.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The Americans captured a large number of German rocket scientists, including Wernher von Braun, in 1945, and brought them to the United States as part of Operation Paperclip.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] After World War II scientists used rockets to study high-altitude conditions, by radio telemetry of temperature and pressure of the atmosphere, detection of cosmic rays, and further techniques; note too the Bell X-1, the first crewed vehicle to break the sound barrier (1947).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Independently, in the Soviet Union's space program research continued under the leadership of the chief designer Sergei Korolev (1907–1966).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] During the Cold War rockets became extremely important militarily with the development of modern intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The 1960s saw rapid development of rocket technology, particularly in the Soviet Union (Vostok, Soyuz, Proton) and in the United States (e.g. the X-15).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rockets came into use for space exploration.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] American crewed programs (Project Mercury, Project Gemini and later the Apollo programme) culminated in 1969 with the first crewed landing on the Moon – using equipment launched by the Saturn V rocket.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] A rocket design can be as simple as a cardboard tube filled with black powder, but to make an efficient, accurate rocket or missile involves overcoming a number of difficult problems.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The main difficulties include cooling the combustion chamber, pumping the fuel (in the case of a liquid fuel), and controlling and correcting the direction of motion.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rockets consist of a propellant, a place to put propellant (such as a propellant tank), and a nozzle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] They may also have one or more rocket engines, directional stabilization device(s) (such as fins, vernier engines or engine gimbals for thrust vectoring, gyroscopes) and a structure (typically monocoque) to hold these components together.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rockets intended for high speed atmospheric use also have an aerodynamic fairing such as a nose cone, which usually holds the payload.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] As well as these components, rockets can have any number of other components, such as wings (rocketplanes), parachutes, wheels (rocket cars), even, in a sense, a person (rocket belt).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Vehicles frequently possess navigation systems and guidance systems that typically use satellite navigation and inertial navigation systems.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rocket engines employ the principle of jet propulsion.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The rocket engines powering rockets come in a great variety of different types; a comprehensive list can be found in the main article, Rocket engine.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Most current rockets are chemically powered rockets (usually internal combustion engines, but some employ a decomposing monopropellant) that emit a hot exhaust gas.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] A rocket engine can use gas propellants, solid propellant, liquid propellant, or a hybrid mixture of both solid and liquid.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Some rockets use heat or pressure that is supplied from a source other than the chemical reaction of propellant(s), such as steam rockets, solar thermal rockets, nuclear thermal rocket engines or simple pressurized rockets such as water rocket or cold gas thrusters.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] With combustive propellants a chemical reaction is initiated between the fuel and the oxidizer in the combustion chamber, and the resultant hot gases accelerate out of a rocket engine nozzle (or nozzles) at the rearward-facing end of the rocket.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The acceleration of these gases through the engine exerts force ("thrust") on the combustion chamber and nozzle, propelling the vehicle (according to Newton's third law).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This actually happens because the force (pressure times area) on the combustion chamber wall is unbalanced by the nozzle opening; this is not the case in any other direction.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The shape of the nozzle also generates force by directing the exhaust gas along the axis of the rocket.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rocket propellant is mass that is stored, usually in some form of propellant tank or casing, prior to being used as the propulsive mass that is ejected from a rocket engine in the form of a fluid jet to produce thrust.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] For chemical rockets often the propellants are a fuel such as liquid hydrogen or kerosene burned with an oxidizer such as liquid oxygen or nitric acid to produce large volumes of very hot gas.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The oxidiser is either kept separate and mixed in the combustion chamber, or comes premixed, as with solid rockets.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Sometimes the propellant is not burned but still undergoes a chemical reaction, and can be a 'monopropellant' such as hydrazine, nitrous oxide or hydrogen peroxide that can be catalytically decomposed to hot gas.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Alternatively, an inert propellant can be used that can be externally heated, such as in steam rocket, solar thermal rocket or nuclear thermal rockets.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] For smaller, low performance rockets such as attitude control thrusters where high performance is less necessary, a pressurised fluid is used as propellant that simply escapes the spacecraft through a propelling nozzle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The first liquid-fuel rocket, constructed by Robert H.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Goddard, differed significantly from modern rockets.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The rocket engine was at the top and the fuel tank at the bottom of the rocket, based on Goddard's belief that the rocket would achieve stability by "hanging" from the engine like a pendulum in flight.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] However, the rocket veered off course and crashed 184 feet (56 m) away from the launch site, indicating that the rocket was no more stable than one with the rocket engine at the base.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rockets or other similar reaction devices carrying their own propellant must be used when there is no other substance (land, water, or air) or force (gravity, magnetism, light) that a vehicle may usefully employ for propulsion, such as in space.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In these circumstances, it is necessary to carry all the propellant to be used.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Some military weapons use rockets to propel warheads to their targets.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] A rocket and its payload together are generally referred to as a *missile* when the weapon has a guidance system (not all missiles use rocket engines, some use other engines such as jets) or as a *rocket* if it is unguided.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Anti-tank and anti-aircraft missiles use rocket engines to engage targets at high speed at a range of several miles, while intercontinental ballistic missiles can be used to deliver multiple nuclear warheads from thousands of miles, and anti-ballistic missiles try to stop them.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rockets have also been tested for reconnaissance, such as the Ping-Pong rocket, which was launched to surveil enemy targets, however, recon rockets have never come into wide use in the military.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Sounding rockets are commonly used to carry instruments that take readings from 50 kilometers (31 mi) to 1,500 kilometers (930 mi) above the surface of the Earth.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The first images of Earth from space were obtained from a V-2 rocket in 1946 (flight #13).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rocket engines are also used to propel rocket sleds along a rail at extremely high speed.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Larger rockets are normally launched from a launch pad that provides stable support until a few seconds after ignition.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Due to their high exhaust velocity—2,500 to 4,500 m/s (9,000 to 16,200 km/h; 5,600 to 10,100 mph)—rockets are particularly useful when very high speeds are required, such as orbital speed at approximately 7,800 m/s (28,000 km/h; 17,000 mph).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Spacecraft delivered into orbital trajectories become artificial satellites, which are used for many commercial purposes.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Indeed, rockets remain the only way to launch spacecraft into orbit and beyond.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] They are also used to rapidly accelerate spacecraft when they change orbits or de-orbit for landing.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Also, a rocket may be used to soften a hard parachute landing immediately before touchdown (see retrorocket).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rockets were used to propel a line to a stricken ship so that a Breeches buoy can be used to rescue those on board.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rockets are also used to launch emergency flares.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Some crewed rockets, notably the Saturn V and Soyuz, have launch escape systems.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This is a small, usually solid rocket that is capable of pulling the crewed capsule away from the main vehicle towards safety at a moments notice.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] These types of systems have been operated several times, both in testing and in flight, and operated correctly each time.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This was the case when the Safety Assurance System (Soviet nomenclature) successfully pulled away the L3 capsule during three of the four failed launches of the Soviet Moon rocket, N1 vehicles 3L, 5L and 7L.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In all three cases the capsule, albeit uncrewed, was saved from destruction.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Only the three aforementioned N1 rockets had functional Safety Assurance Systems.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The outstanding vehicle, 6L, had dummy upper stages and therefore no escape system giving the N1 booster a 100% success rate for egress from a failed launch.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] A successful escape of a crewed capsule occurred when Soyuz T-10, on a mission to the Salyut 7 space station, exploded on the pad.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Solid rocket propelled ejection seats are used in many military aircraft to propel crew away to safety from a vehicle when flight control is lost.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] A model rocket is a small rocket designed to reach low altitudes (e.g., 100–500 m (330–1,640 ft) for 30 g (1.1 oz) model) and be recovered by a variety of means.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] According to the United States National Association of Rocketry (nar) Safety Code, model rockets are constructed of paper, wood, plastic and other lightweight materials.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The code also provides guidelines for motor use, launch site selection, launch methods, launcher placement, recovery system design and deployment and more.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Since the early 1960s, a copy of the Model Rocket Safety Code has been provided with most model rocket kits and motors.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Hobbyists build and fly a wide variety of model rockets.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Many companies produce model rocket kits and parts but due to their inherent simplicity some hobbyists have been known to make rockets out of almost anything.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rockets are also used in some types of consumer and professional fireworks.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] A water rocket is a type of model rocket using water as its reaction mass.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The pressure vessel (the engine of the rocket) is usually a used plastic soft drink bottle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The water is forced out by a pressurized gas, typically compressed air.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] It is an example of Newton's third law of motion.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The scale of amateur rocketry can range from a small rocket launched in one's own backyard to a rocket that reached space.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Amateur rocketry is split into three categories according to total engine impulse: low-power, mid-power, and high-power.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Hydrogen peroxide rockets are used to power jet packs, and have been used to power cars and a rocket car holds the all time (albeit unofficial) drag racing record.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Corpulent Stump is the most powerful non-commercial rocket ever launched on an Aerotech engine in the United Kingdom.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Launches for orbital spaceflights, or into interplanetary space, are usually from a fixed location on the ground, but would also be possible from an aircraft or ship.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rocket launch technologies include the entire set of systems needed to successfully launch a vehicle, not just the vehicle itself, but also the firing control systems, mission control centre, launch pad, ground stations, and tracking stations needed for a successful launch or recovery or both.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] These are often collectively referred to as the "ground segment".
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Orbital launch vehicles commonly take off vertically, and then begin to progressively lean over, usually following a gravity turn trajectory.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Once above the majority of the atmosphere, the vehicle then angles the rocket jet, pointing it largely horizontally but somewhat downwards, which permits the vehicle to gain and then maintain altitude while increasing horizontal speed.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] As the speed grows, the vehicle will become more and more horizontal until at orbital speed, the engine will cut off.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] All current vehicles *stage*, that is, jettison hardware on the way to orbit.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Although vehicles have been proposed which would be able to reach orbit without staging, none have ever been constructed, and, if powered only by rockets, the exponentially increasing fuel requirements of such a vehicle would make its useful payload tiny or nonexistent.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Most current and historical launch vehicles "expend" their jettisoned hardware, typically by allowing it to crash into the ocean, but some have recovered and reused jettisoned hardware, either by parachute or by propulsive landing.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] When launching a spacecraft to orbit, a "dogleg" is a guided, powered turn during ascent phase that causes a rocket's flight path to deviate from a "straight" path.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] A dogleg is necessary if the desired launch azimuth, to reach a desired orbital inclination, would take the ground track over land (or over a populated area, e.g.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Russia usually does launch over land, but over unpopulated areas), or if the rocket is trying to reach an orbital plane that does not reach the latitude of the launch site.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Doglegs are undesirable due to extra onboard fuel required, causing heavier load, and a reduction of vehicle performance.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rocket exhaust generates a significant amount of acoustic energy.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] As the supersonic exhaust collides with the ambient air, shock waves are formed.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The sound intensity from these shock waves depends on the size of the rocket as well as the exhaust velocity.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The sound intensity of large, high performance rockets could potentially kill at close range.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The Space Shuttle generated 180 dB of noise around its base.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] To combat this, NASA developed a sound suppression system which can flow water at rates up to 900,000 gallons per minute (57 m3/s) onto the launch pad.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The water reduces the noise level from 180 dB down to 142 dB (the design requirement is 145 dB).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Without the sound suppression system, acoustic waves would reflect off of the launch pad towards the rocket, vibrating the sensitive payload and crew.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] These acoustic waves can be so severe as to damage or destroy the rocket.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Noise is generally most intense when a rocket is close to the ground, since the noise from the engines radiates up away from the jet, as well as reflecting off the ground.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This noise can be reduced somewhat by flame trenches with roofs, by water injection around the jet and by deflecting the jet at an angle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] For crewed rockets various methods are used to reduce the sound intensity for the passengers, and typically the placement of the astronauts far away from the rocket engines helps significantly.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] For the passengers and crew, when a vehicle goes supersonic the sound cuts off as the sound waves are no longer able to keep up with the vehicle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The effect of the combustion of propellant in the rocket engine is to increase the internal energy of the resulting gases, utilizing the stored chemical energy in the fuel.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] As the internal energy increases, pressure increases, and a nozzle is used to convert this energy into a directed kinetic energy.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This produces thrust against the ambient environment to which these gases are released.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The ideal direction of motion of the exhaust is in the direction so as to cause thrust.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] At the top end of the combustion chamber the hot, energetic gas fluid cannot move forward, and so, it pushes upward against the top of the rocket engine's combustion chamber.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] As the combustion gases approach the exit of the combustion chamber, they increase in speed.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The effect of the convergent part of the rocket engine nozzle on the high pressure fluid of combustion gases, is to cause the gases to accelerate to high speed.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The higher the speed of the gases, the lower the pressure of the gas (Bernoulli's principle or conservation of energy) acting on that part of the combustion chamber.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In a properly designed engine, the flow will reach Mach 1 at the throat of the nozzle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] At which point the speed of the flow increases.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Beyond the throat of the nozzle, a bell shaped expansion part of the engine allows the gases that are expanding to push against that part of the rocket engine.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Thus, the bell part of the nozzle gives additional thrust.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Simply expressed, for every action there is an equal and opposite reaction, according to Newton's third law with the result that the exiting gases produce the reaction of a force on the rocket causing it to accelerate the rocket.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In a closed chamber, the pressures are equal in each direction and no acceleration occurs.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] If an opening is provided in the bottom of the chamber then the pressure is no longer acting on the missing section.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This opening permits the exhaust to escape.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The remaining pressures give a resultant thrust on the side opposite the opening, and these pressures are what push the rocket along.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Consider a balloon propelled by air coming out of a tapering nozzle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In such a case the combination of air pressure and viscous friction is such that the nozzle does not push the balloon but is *pulled* by it.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Using a convergent/divergent nozzle gives more force since the exhaust also presses on it as it expands outwards, roughly doubling the total force.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] If propellant gas is continuously added to the chamber then these pressures can be maintained for as long as propellant remains.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Note that in the case of liquid propellant engines, the pumps moving the propellant into the combustion chamber must maintain a pressure larger than the combustion chamber—typically on the order of 100 atmospheres.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] As a side effect, these pressures on the rocket also act on the exhaust in the opposite direction and accelerate this exhaust to very high speeds (according to Newton's third law).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] From the principle of conservation of momentum the speed of the exhaust of a rocket determines how much momentum increase is created for a given amount of propellant.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This is called the rocket's *specific impulse*.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Because a rocket, propellant and exhaust in flight, without any external perturbations, may be considered as a closed system, the total momentum is always constant.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Therefore, the faster the net speed of the exhaust in one direction, the greater the speed of the rocket can achieve in the opposite direction.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This is especially true since the rocket body's mass is typically far lower than the final total exhaust mass.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The general study of the forces on a rocket is part of the field of ballistics.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Spacecraft are further studied in the subfield of astrodynamics.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In addition, the inertia and centrifugal pseudo-force can be significant due to the path of the rocket around the centre of a celestial body; when high enough speeds in the right direction and altitude are achieved a stable orbit or escape velocity is obtained.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] These forces, with a stabilizing tail (the *empennage*) present will, unless deliberate control efforts are made, naturally cause the vehicle to follow a roughly parabolic trajectory termed a gravity turn, and this trajectory is often used at least during the initial part of a launch.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] (This is true even if the rocket engine is mounted at the nose.) Vehicles can thus maintain low or even zero angle of attack, which minimizes transverse stress on the launch vehicle, permitting a weaker, and hence lighter, launch vehicle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Drag is a force opposite to the direction of the rocket's motion relative to any air it is moving through.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This slows the speed of the vehicle and produces structural loads.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The deceleration forces for fast-moving rockets are calculated using the drag equation.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Drag can be minimised by an aerodynamic nose cone and by using a shape with a high ballistic coefficient (the "classic" rocket shape—long and thin), and by keeping the rocket's angle of attack as low as possible.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] During a launch, as the vehicle speed increases, and the atmosphere thins, there is a point of maximum aerodynamic drag called max Q.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This determines the minimum aerodynamic strength of the vehicle, as the rocket must avoid buckling under these forces.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] A typical rocket engine can handle a significant fraction of its own mass in propellant each second, with the propellant leaving the nozzle at several kilometres per second.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This means that the thrust-to-weight ratio of a rocket engine, and often the entire vehicle can be very high, in extreme cases over 100.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This compares with other jet propulsion engines that can exceed 5 for some of the better engines.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The effective exhaust velocity $v_{e}$ is more or less the speed the exhaust leaves the vehicle, and in the vacuum of space, the effective exhaust velocity is often equal to the actual average exhaust speed along the thrust axis.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] However, the effective exhaust velocity allows for various losses, and notably, is reduced when operated within an atmosphere.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The rate of propellant flow through a rocket engine is often deliberately varied over a flight, to provide a way to control the thrust and thus the airspeed of the vehicle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This, for example, allows minimization of aerodynamic losses and can limit the increase of *g*-forces due to the reduction in propellant load.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Impulse is defined as a force acting on an object over time, which in the absence of opposing forces (gravity and aerodynamic drag), changes the momentum (integral of mass and velocity) of the object.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] As such, it is the best performance class (payload mass and terminal velocity capability) indicator of a rocket, rather than takeoff thrust, mass, or "power".
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The total impulse of a multi-stage rocket is the sum of the impulses of the individual stages.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] As can be seen from the thrust equation, the effective speed of the exhaust controls the amount of thrust produced from a particular quantity of fuel burnt per second.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] An equivalent measure, the net impulse per weight unit of propellant expelled, is called specific Impulse, $I_{sp}$ , and this is one of the most important figures that describes a rocket's performance.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Thus, the greater the specific impulse, the greater the net thrust and performance of the engine. $I_{sp}$ is determined by measurement while testing the engine.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In practice the effective exhaust velocities of rockets varies but can be extremely high, ~4500 m/s, about 15 times the sea level speed of sound in air.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The delta-v capacity of a rocket is the theoretical total change in velocity that a rocket can achieve without any external interference (without air drag or gravity or other forces).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] When launched from the Earth practical delta-vs for a single rockets carrying payloads can be a few km/s.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Some theoretical designs have rockets with delta-vs over 9 km/s.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The required delta-v can also be calculated for a particular manoeuvre; for example the delta-v to launch from the surface of the Earth to low Earth orbit is about 9.7 km/s, which leaves the vehicle with a sideways speed of about 7.8 km/s at an altitude of around 200 km.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In this manoeuvre about 1.9 km/s is lost in air drag, gravity drag and gaining altitude.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The ratio ${\frac {m_{0}}{m_{1}}}$ is sometimes called the *mass ratio*.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Almost all of a launch vehicle's mass consists of propellant.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Mass ratio is, for any 'burn', the ratio between the rocket's initial mass and its final mass.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Everything else being equal, a high mass ratio is desirable for good performance, since it indicates that the rocket is lightweight and hence performs better, for essentially the same reasons that low weight is desirable in sports cars.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Rockets as a group have the highest thrust-to-weight ratio of any type of engine; and this helps vehicles achieve high mass ratios, which improves the performance of flights.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The higher the ratio, the less engine mass is needed to be carried.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This permits the carrying of even more propellant, enormously improving the delta-v.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Alternatively, some rockets such as for rescue scenarios or racing carry relatively little propellant and payload and thus need only a lightweight structure and instead achieve high accelerations.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] For example, the Soyuz escape system can produce 20 *g*.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Achievable mass ratios are highly dependent on many factors such as propellant type, the design of engine the vehicle uses, structural safety margins and construction techniques.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The highest mass ratios are generally achieved with liquid rockets, and these types are usually used for orbital launch vehicles, a situation which calls for a high delta-v.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Liquid propellants generally have densities similar to water (with the notable exceptions of liquid hydrogen and liquid methane), and these types are able to use lightweight, low pressure tanks and typically run high-performance turbopumps to force the propellant into the combustion chamber.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Since Single-stage-to-orbit has so far not been achievable, orbital rockets always have more than one stage.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] For example, the first stage of the Saturn V, carrying the weight of the upper stages, was able to achieve a mass ratio of about 10, and achieved a specific impulse of 263 seconds.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This gives a delta-v of around 5.9 km/s whereas around 9.4 km/s delta-v is needed to achieve orbit with all losses allowed for.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This problem is frequently solved by staging—the rocket sheds excess weight (usually empty tankage and associated engines) during launch.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Staging is either *serial* where the rockets light after the previous stage has fallen away, or *parallel*, where rockets are burning together and then detach when they burn out.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The maximum speeds that can be achieved with staging is theoretically limited only by the speed of light.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] However the payload that can be carried goes down geometrically with each extra stage needed, while the additional delta-v for each stage is simply additive.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] where m is the instantaneous mass of the vehicle and $F_{n}$ is the net force acting on the rocket (mostly thrust, but air drag and other forces can play a part).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] As the remaining propellant decreases, rocket vehicles become lighter and their acceleration tends to increase until the propellant is exhausted.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This means that much of the speed change occurs towards the end of the burn when the vehicle is much lighter.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] However, the thrust can be throttled to offset or vary this if needed.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Discontinuities in acceleration also occur when stages burn out, often starting at a lower acceleration with each new stage firing.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Peak accelerations can be increased by designing the vehicle with a reduced mass, usually achieved by a reduction in the fuel load and tankage and associated structures, but obviously this reduces range, delta-v and burn time.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Still, for some applications that rockets are used for, a high peak acceleration applied for just a short time is highly desirable.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The minimal mass of vehicle consists of a rocket engine with minimal fuel and structure to carry it.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In that case the thrust-to-weight ratio of the rocket engine limits the maximum acceleration that can be designed.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] It turns out that rocket engines generally have truly excellent thrust to weight ratios (137 for the NK-33 engine; some solid rockets are over 1000), and nearly all really high-g vehicles employ or have employed rockets.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The high accelerations that rockets naturally possess means that rocket vehicles are often capable of vertical takeoff, and in some cases, with suitable guidance and control of the engines, also vertical landing.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] For these operations to be done it is necessary for a vehicle's engines to provide more than the local gravitational acceleration.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The energy density of a typical rocket propellant is often around one-third that of conventional hydrocarbon fuels; the bulk of the mass is (often relatively inexpensive) oxidizer.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Nevertheless, at take-off the rocket has a great deal of energy in the fuel and oxidizer stored within the vehicle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] It is of course desirable that as much of the energy of the propellant end up as kinetic or potential energy of the body of the rocket as possible.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Energy from the fuel is lost in air drag and gravity drag and is used for the rocket to gain altitude and speed.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] However, much of the lost energy ends up in the exhaust.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] 100% efficiency within the engine (engine efficiency $\eta _{c}=100\%$ ) would mean that all the heat energy of the combustion products is converted into kinetic energy of the jet.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This is not possible, but the near-adiabatic high expansion ratio nozzles that can be used with rockets come surprisingly close: when the nozzle expands the gas, the gas is cooled and accelerated, and an energy efficiency of up to 70% can be achieved.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Most of the rest is heat energy in the exhaust that is not recovered.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The high efficiency is a consequence of the fact that rocket combustion can be performed at very high temperatures and the gas is finally released at much lower temperatures, and so giving good Carnot efficiency.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] However, engine efficiency is not the whole story.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In common with the other jet-based engines, but particularly in rockets due to their high and typically fixed exhaust speeds, rocket vehicles are extremely inefficient at low speeds irrespective of the engine efficiency.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The problem is that at low speeds, the exhaust carries away a huge amount of kinetic energy rearward.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This phenomenon is termed propulsive efficiency ( $\eta _{p}$ ).
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] However, as speeds rise, the resultant exhaust speed goes down, and the overall vehicle energetic efficiency rises, reaching a peak of around 100% of the engine efficiency when the vehicle is travelling exactly at the same speed that the exhaust is emitted.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] In this case the exhaust would ideally stop dead in space behind the moving vehicle, taking away zero energy, and from conservation of energy, all the energy would end up in the vehicle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] The efficiency then drops off again at even higher speeds as the exhaust ends up travelling forwards – trailing behind the vehicle.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Thus a rocket would need about 6× more energy; and allowing for the specific energy of rocket propellant being around one third that of conventional air fuel, roughly 18× more mass of propellant would need to be carried for the same journey.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This is why rockets are rarely if ever used for general aviation.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Since the energy ultimately comes from fuel, these considerations mean that rockets are mainly useful when a very high speed is required, such as ICBMs or orbital launch.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] At this altitude and velocity, the vehicle had a kinetic energy of about 3 TJ and a potential energy of roughly 200 GJ.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Given the initial energy of 20 TJ, the Space Shuttle was about 16% energy efficient at launching the orbiter.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] Thus jet engines, with a better match between speed and jet exhaust speed (such as turbofans—in spite of their worse $\eta _{c}$ )—dominate for subsonic and supersonic atmospheric use, while rockets work best at hypersonic speeds.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] On the other hand, rockets serve in many short-range *relatively* low speed military applications where their low-speed inefficiency is outweighed by their extremely high thrust and hence high accelerations.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] One subtle feature of rockets relates to energy.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] A rocket stage, while carrying a given load, is capable of giving a particular delta-v.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This delta-v means that the speed increases (or decreases) by a particular amount, independent of the initial speed.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] However, because kinetic energy is a square law on speed, this means that the faster the rocket is travelling before the burn the more orbital energy it gains or loses.
[src:rocket/rocket-p01] This fact is used in interplanetary travel.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] The reliability of rockets, as for all physical systems, is dependent on the quality of engineering design and construction.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] Because of the enormous chemical energy in rocket propellants (greater energy by weight than explosives, but lower than gasoline), consequences of accidents can be severe.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] Most space missions have some problems; for example, a cabin fire during a launch rehearsal of the 1967 Apollo I spacecraft killed all three crew members.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] The costs of rockets can be roughly divided into propellant costs, the costs of obtaining and/or producing the 'dry mass' of the rocket, and the costs of any required support equipment and facilities.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] Most of the takeoff mass of a rocket is normally propellant.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] Even though a rocket's non-propellant, dry mass is often only between 5–20% of total mass, nevertheless this cost dominates.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] For hardware with the performance used in orbital launch vehicles, expenses of $2000–$10,000+ per kilogram of dry weight are common, primarily from engineering, fabrication, and testing; raw materials amount to typically around 2% of total expense.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] For most rockets except reusable ones (shuttle engines) the engines need not function more than a few minutes, which simplifies design.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] Extreme performance requirements for rockets reaching orbit correlate with high cost, including intensive quality control to ensure reliability despite the limited safety factors allowable for weight reasons.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] Components produced in small numbers if not individually machined can prevent amortization of R&D and facility costs over mass production to the degree seen in more pedestrian manufacturing.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] The costs of support equipment, range costs and launch pads generally scale up with the size of the rocket, but vary less with launch rate, and so may be considered to be approximately a fixed cost.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] Rockets in applications other than launch to orbit (such as military rockets and rocket-assisted take off), commonly not needing comparable performance and sometimes mass-produced, are often relatively inexpensive.
[src:rocket/rocket-p02] Since the early 2010s, new private options for obtaining spaceflight services emerged, bringing substantial price pressure into the existing market.
